<SECOND>PM-Florida Lottery,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>859 People, One Newspaper Have Winning Florida Lottery Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petersburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> had a winning ticket but no winners in the fledgling <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lottery's first computerized numbers game. A photo at the top of the front page of Friday morning's newspaper showed the numbers 8-0-6, which turned out to be the winning combination in the first Cash 3 contest that night The photo, used to illustrate a story about the lottery, was of a sample ticket sent to the paper a month ago. `` This was entirely coincidental,'' City Editor <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said. `` It does n't seem like that should need to be said, but we've gotten so many calls. The first daily contest produced 859 winners but none in the Times newsroom. `` In fact, I do n't know anyone that played daily game in the newsroom,'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said. A spokesman for the lottery said the first Cash 3 game drawing went off without a hitch. Pingpong balls with the winning numbers were selected in only 60 seconds. The payout totaled $ 94,090. Ticket sales are expected to top $ 10 million in the first week. By 7:30 p.m. Friday, $ 616,543 had been wagered on Cash 3 and $ 345,377 on the jackpot Lotto game. Thirty-five percent of all lottery revenues are earmarked for public education. The first Lotto drawing will be held May 7. The prize will be at least $ 2 million but could reach $ 4 million. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> joins 27 other states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> that have legalized lotteries. Law enforcement officials hope the legalized <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> numbers games will help undermine illegal numbers rackets.
