<SECOND>PM-China-Youth Crime,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juveniles Cause Two-Thirds of Crimes in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Juveniles cause more than 60 percent of the crime in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> the crimes they commit are becoming more violent, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The newspaper quoted <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jian </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juvenile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delinquency </ORGANIZATION>, as saying the rate of juvenile crime is 12 per 10,000 of the same age group. He said that was more than double the overall crime rate of 5 per 10,000 people, but still much lower than in developed countries. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> gave no figures for juvenile crimes or what age group is classified as juveniles. He said youths who in the past mainly committed minor offenses such as petty thefts and fighting are now engaged in robberies, violent assaults and rapes. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> attributed the rise in juvenile crime to the lack of proper laws, the spread of pornography, the increasing numbers of working parents and divorce. Girls, mainly involved in hooliganism _ a general term for unsocial behavior _ or sex crimes, made up 18.6 percent of juvenile criminals in 1985, up from 10 percent in 1983, he said. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> said juvenile delinquency would continue to rise in the near future and called for a national network to educate and prevent youths from committing crimes.
