<FIRST>r i PM-OPEC     04-30 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OPEC,0672</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Proposed Oil Deal Hinges On Saudi Assent</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> moved one major step closer today to an agreement that could slightly increase oil prices and set the stage for closer coordination with oil producers outside its ranks. But clinching the deal required the approval of oil ministers from <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and its three <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> allies, who said they needed to consult their governments first. A meeting of all <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil ministers was set for tonight at cartel headquarters, but it was not certain a final decision would be made then. Eight of the 13 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> agreed in a meeting that ended early today to a proposed 2 percent cut in <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s total oil production, according to oil ministers from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The cuts would be for May and June only, said Venezuelan Oil Minister <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Grisanti </PERSON>. The Saudis earlier indicated they opposed production cuts, believing prices would rebound soon anyway since oil demand is likely to rise this summer. Saudi King <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON> said in a newspaper interview Thursday that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> should simply stick to its current set of production quotas, which often are exceeded. He did not explicitly rule out cuts as small as those proposed in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. Besides <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the others saying they wanted to think it over were <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which is not party to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s existing agreement on production limits, was not expected to take part in the proposed cuts, <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said. The eight that tentatively accepted the deal this morning were <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. The proposal was put on the table by <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. The proposed cuts in output, in conjunction with similarly small cuts by a group of six independent oil-producing nations, would remove a total of 500,000 barrels a day from the world oil market. The goal is to lift oil prices to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s target of $ 18 a 42-gallon barrel from the range now of between $ 14 and $ 16. Oil prices on the open market moved erratically in nervous trading Friday. Prices fell more than 60 cents a barrel in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but recovered in later <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, June contracts for West Texas Intermediate, the main <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grade of oil, closed at $ 17.99 a barrel, up one cent from Thursday. At one point, the price was off 43 cents but then recovered. The proposed <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> cuts are so small that analysts said the main effect on the market would be psychological. For <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>, the principal benefit would be establishing closer ties to rival oil producers, who in recent years have weakened <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> by taking away its market share. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and non-OPEC producers have never before formally agreed to mutual cuts in production, although <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has informally sought to align its policies with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>. The non-OPEC countries involved in the current proposal are <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Representatives of these independent producers were in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> earlier this week for talks with a committee of six <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> oil ministers. They left before <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s meeting began Thursday, so it was not immediately clear if they would be satisfied with the proposed cut of 2 percent, or 300,000 barrels a day, in <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production. The non-OPEC group stipulated it would cut its oil exports by 5 percent, or 200,000 barrels a day, only if <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> made `` similar, proportional'' reductions. It was not more precise about the reciprocity. Regardless of the outcome of the talks on production cuts, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> intended to step up contacts with the non-OPEC group in hopes of establishing a regular dialogue that could lead to more coordination of production and pricing policy in the future, several oil ministers said. `` We must send a positive signal to them,'' said <PERSON> Gholamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aghazadeh </PERSON>, the oil minister of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>.
