<SECOND>PM-Defense Spending, 610</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Rejects Threat Of Pullout To Increase Allied Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House says the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration ought to talk with <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> about spending more for defense, but has rejected calls to bring <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops home if that is n't done. The decisions were part of the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s effort to write a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 359-0 late Friday afternoon to approve a proposal calling for the administration to initiate talks with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> member nations about sharing the burden for defense. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote came as the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> released its 1988 report on `` Allied Contributions to the Common Defense,'' an annual assessment mandated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The report was accompanied by a personal pledge from <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> to `` press at every opportunity for progress'' in sharing the burdens of the alliance. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the report's `` principal conclusion'' is that the allies are making more of a contribution than they receive credit for, but he said `` there are substantial variations in performance among individual allies.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote echoed a similar proposal approved last summer by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but the administration has n't yet pushed hard for the talks. Both <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members have criticized <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for failing to spend more on defense. They note that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spends about 6.9 percent of its gross national product on defense, a far larger share than other western nations. Despite the criticism, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has refused for three years to order sanctions against <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the alliance, a refusal that was continued Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has about 326,000 troops stationed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and 63,000 in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. By a 240-120 vote, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected a proposal by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, to bring 30,000 troops a year back from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and 7,000 troops a year from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> starting in 1991. Minutes later it voted 332-21 to reject a plan by Rep. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., to withdraw 70,000 troops a year from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` Let's get smart and begin to tell our allies that we expect them to pay their fair share,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. `` We are subsidizing their defense.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> made a similar appeal, telling his colleagues: `` The real purpose of this amendment is to demonstrate to our allies that we've had it. These people are stealing our jobs because we have been suckered into paying for their defense.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON>, R-Pa., said the issue should be `` considered in a clear process and not on an emotional basis. `` It is simply not possible to maintain the viability of a voluntary alliance of free countries if one of those countries tries to impose standards on the others,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N </LOCATION>. But Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, D-Wis., said, `` It's time Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> quit being taken for Uncle Sucker. The spending bill would authorize the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to spend $ 299.5 billion in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, which is the same amount proposed by the separate bill that will be considered next month by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. Differences between the bills eventually will be reconciled by a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> report said that the 6.1 percent of gross national product spent by <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> for defense in 1986 was the closest to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share. <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> was third with 5.1 percent, followed by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> at 4.8 percent and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> at 3.9 percent. `` All of the remaining nations have shares of 3.2 percent or less,'' the study found. The report used 1986 data because that is the most recent year for which figures were available.
