<FIRST>r w PM-Durenberger-Espionage     04-30 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durenberger-Espionage,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee Chastises Durenberger On Espionage Disclosure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ethics panel says comments by Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> on an espionage case hurt relations between <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and intelligence agencies, but <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> says the harm already had been done by the late <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>. <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> was chastised Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> as it closed an investigation that began last year after the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Republican publicly discussed an espionage case involving the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The committee told <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> in a letter: `` The <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has determined that your statements gave the appearance that you were disclosing sensitive national security information and such appearance jeopardized the mutual confidence which must exist between the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the intelligence community. ... `` Because the committee has concluded that your actions were not intentional, deliberate, nor attended with gross negligence, and because of the particular facts of this case, we will not recommend that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> take institutional action against you. However, the committee wants to make it clear that it does not condone your actions.'' The ethics investigation centered on comments <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> made at an event sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, on March 15, 1987. <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> reportedly disclosed to the group that <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> in 1982 had `` changed the rules'' under which allies did not spy on each other by recruiting an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> military officer to spy on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON>'s comments were said to be aimed at giving context to the case of <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollard </PERSON>, an American convicted of spying on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Durenberger </PERSON> said he based his remarks on newspaper accounts and maintained that he exercised `` due care'' in preparation for the speech. The former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement saying he was pleased that the committee had concluded its investigation and determined that no action was necessary. But he added: `` The late <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s fundamental disagreement over the philosophy of congressional oversight led to frequent clashes with the <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` Director <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> was a strong leader, loyal to his own view of the public interest, but his belief that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should play little or no role in intelligence oversight led to a lack of mutual confidence long before March 1987.'' He added, `` I respectfully disagree with the ethic committee's conclusion that my statements gave the appearance that I was disclosing sensitive information. Sources present at the <LOCATION> Palm </LOC