<HEAD>Agency Issues Long-Awaited Regulations On Idled Machinery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> wants employers to put warning tags on machinery that has been shut off to prevent injuries and deaths caused when the machines are turned on while being cleaned or serviced. Nine years and 1,000 deaths after unions first pleaded for action on one of the single biggest causes of industrial accidents, the agency issued proposed regulations Friday on so-called `` tagouts'' and `` lockouts.'' The proposals appeared in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION> a week after <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., said the delay showed the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's `` decision to let workers die while waiting on a standard. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials testified last week at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing chaired by <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> that the proposed regulations had been completed by the agency in early 1987 but had languished at the White House for nearly a year. About 7 percent of all occupational fatalities and 2 per cent of accident-caused injuries in the workplace occur now because such equipment is inadvertently restarted while someone is working on it. The agency estimated Friday that the so-called `` performance-oriented'' regulations will save 122 lives and prevent 60,000 job injuries a year. But they would require employers only to follow certain steps in turning off equipment and `` minimize'' the potential for inadvertently reactivating it. `` Very simple lockout, tagout measures, which taken only a few minutes, can prevent up to 10 percent of all the serious injuries in some major manufacturing industries,'' said Assistant Labor Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON>. Agency officials estimated it will be a minimum of another year before the regulations are actually enacted. Unions had begun petitioning the agency for the regulations in 1979. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Molovich </PERSON>, a safety specialist for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, predicted employers will ignore the guidelines and `` take the cheapest way out'' by using cardboard warning tags instead of locks to prevent a machine from being turned on. `` There will be no positive means of assuring that the equipment wo n't start,'' he said. The regulations, if adopted in current form, will apply to only 1.6 million employers and cover only 39 million workers, most of them in manufacturing. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> estimated the annual cost of compliance to businesses at $ 135 million. Exempted are millions of companies and workers in agriculture, oil and gas drilling, electric utilities, the maritime industry and construction. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said protections for them will be included in other regulations to be proposed later. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> official who worked on the regulations for more than a decade, testified at the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearings last week that the agency had first seen a need for them back in 1977. But <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> took no serious action until 1979, when the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, reacting to the deaths of 22 of its members in related accidents the previous five years, formally asked the government for emergency action. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> denied that request and similar pleas in 1982 and 1986 from other unions.
</TEXT>
