<HEAD>Mobster Says ``We Don't Kill Innocent People''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An indicted <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> mobster says <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cosa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nostra </LOCATION> families use murder to enforce their internal rules, but insists, `` We do n't kill innocent people.'' <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> `` The Fish'' <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON>, who was a `` soldier'' in the Genovese organized crime family, told senators Friday the organization was `` very disciplined'' and members paid a high price for breaking the rules. `` Killings were mandatory'' for fooling around with another member's wife and dealing in drugs, he said. `` When it comes to an amico nostra's wife or ` junk' there was no talk,'' <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said. An amico nostra is a member of a mob family, and `` junk'' means narcotics. <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said mob members also could get murdered for `` ratting, refusing to go on a ` hit' if asked or knowingly killing a cop or other law enforcement agent.'' To win approval to carry out a murder, <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said, mob members had to go through the chain of command, right up to the boss of the family. But he insisted, `` We do n't kill innocent people.'' Unlike witnesses who spoke from behind a screen, <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> _ a thin, balding man with glasses _ testified in full public view before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Permanent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> on Investigations. He currently is in custody while awaiting trial in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on racketeering, extortion and conspiracy charges. After his arrest in 1986, he cooperated with federal authorities and even carried a concealed microphone while talking to other mobsters. But <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said personal safety concerns have persuaded him to end the effort, and he was heavily guarded in the hearing room. `` I'm fair game, no question about it,'' he said. <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said he had worked for the mob since 1958, as an associate of `` Fat Tony'' <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON>, a major figure in the Genovese family. <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON>, who <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said was `` like a father to me,'' is now on trial in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on charges related to mob activities. <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> also told the committee, headed by Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., that four organized crime families run the high-rise construction industry in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> through control over the concrete industry and construction unions He said bids were rigged, and that contractors and unions winning construction jobs had to kick back 2 percent of the contract price to the mob. <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said the system was arranged through the `` ` 2 <ORGANIZATION> Percent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>,'' an organization run by the Genovese, <PERSON> Gambino </PERSON>, Lucchese and <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> families. He estimated that at least 50 percent of the high-rise construction in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> had a mob connection and added, `` Legitimate guys ai n't got a chance'' to win contracts for those buildings. <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said each of the four mob families had an expert on the construction business in the organization. Members read the Dodge Reports, a construction trade publication that lists upcoming jobs, he said. `` The club members split up all of the jobs over $ 2 million,'' he said. But if the contract went over $ 5 million, it went to a mob-run company, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; A Concrete, he said. When the smaller contractors complained of the arrangement, he said, they won the right to split all jobs over $ 3 million. As a mob soldier who turned down promotions because he did n't want the added responsibility, <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said he preferred to run the numbers business in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> `` I had some bad years, but in a good year I could make as much as $ 2 million or more,'' he said. When <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> asked if he kept the money, <PERSON> Cafaro </PERSON> said: `` I spent it. I gave it away. I loaned a lot of money to people and never got it back.'' The mobster said he only carried cash.
