<HEAD>Senior Prom Returns after 25-Year Hiatus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with prom under way. PICKS UP
2nd graf pvs, `The last ...'; INSERTS three grafs after 10th graf
pvs, `The town ...' to UPDATE with prom underway.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM PARSONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORREST CITY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The senior prom returned to <ORGANIZATION> Forrest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on Friday, more than 25 years after it was banned by school officials. `` I'm gon na do Da Bump,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, an 18-year-old senior, said as he made his appearance at the <ORGANIZATION> Forrest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> dressed all in white but for a black snap-brim hat and black cane. The last prom was in 1962, said <PERSON> Principal </PERSON> <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, who helped plan the last one as a senior class sponsor early in his career. He said he did n't know what had prompted the ban _ `` I was just a teacher at the time'' _ noting that it would n't have been a racial issue because the first black student did n't enter the school until 1965. `` That was before integration. After that, the board voted not to have them any more,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. However, the student council officers decided not to have a king and queen for the new prom partly because the couple might be racially mixed, the <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gazette </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. The newspaper's assertion was disputed by <PERSON> Kaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON>, 17, recording secretary for the council. `` We decided not to have a prom king and queen because we feel that we're all kings and queens,'' she said. `` We talked about it and said, ` No, we do n't want to do that.' More than half the 355 seniors were expected to attend the dance in the <ORGANIZATION> Forrest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, Student Council President <PERSON> Tangella </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. Assistant Principal <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridges </PERSON> said he expected the crowd to be about evenly divided between black and white students, like the composition of the 1,450-student school. `` I do n't think that's even been thought about,'' Bridges said. The town of about 14,000, 45 miles west of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, is about evenly divided between black and white. The boys wore black, white or gray but the colors of the girls' gowns ranged across the spectrum and skirt lengths were anywhere between the ankles and the knees Three couples stepped out of a stretch limouisine from a funeral home, the driver holding the door. Then, at the request of a TV crew, they got back in and did it again. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> McNair </PERSON>, 18, sharply dressed in an Army Junior ROTC uniform, came all the way from <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION>, 125 miles to the west, to escort his cousin, <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 18. Precautions were taken to avoid any problems at the prom, Bridges said. `` There'll be strictly no drinking,'' he said. `` We do n't allow smoking anyway, at the school, so there'll be no smoking at the prom, no drinking, no drugs.'' Students who leave the prom will not be able to return, he said. `` And there wo n't be any press or anything like that,'' Bridges said. `` It's going to be strictly for the kids.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Forrest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> voted last fall to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to sponsor a prom for 1988's graduating seniors. `` We just thought it was time for us to do like other folks,'' school board member <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> said after that meeting. `` It's a milestone,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, a 1967 graduate of the