<HEAD>Condor Chick Hatches With Help From Its Keepers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs to UPDATE with comments from news conference.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, `A recording...' Edits to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condor conceived in captivity hatched Friday, its keepers using tweezers and their fingertips to help the newest member of the nearly extinct species break free from its shell, officials said. `` It's alive and it looks healthy,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanscom </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's resting now. We do n't have any other details.'' The hatching represents a tremendous boost to efforts to save the species. It brings the known population of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest land bird to 28, all in captivity _ 15 at the park here and 13 at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Zoo The squawking infant, named <PERSON> Molloko </PERSON>, an Indian word for `` condor,'' was swaddled in a towel and placed in the same type of incubator used for premature infants. `` Early this morning there were 27 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors left in the world,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Toone </PERSON>, curator of birds at the park. `` This afternoon there's 28 of them, and we could n't be more excited about that. `` When the numbers are so low, one bird is seen as a very big step away from extinction,'' <PERSON> Toone </PERSON> added. Although the tiny bird was not brought forth to `` meet the press,'' its history-making birth was recorded on videotape and shown at a press conference Friday night. Earlier, the chick had become stuck in dried membrane and albumen and could no longer rotate in the shell to peck its way out. Its keepers removed it cautiously because of the danger of rupturing blood vessels linked to egg membranes. A recording of vultures making hissing and grunting sounds was played at intervals to duplicate the sounds the chick would hear in a natural setting. Park officials had said they intended to intervene by Saturday if the chick, which began hatching Wednesday, had n't emerged from the shell. Allowing the hatching struggle to continue would overexhaust the bird. The chick, conceived by the only known activing breeding pair of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condor, was expected to weigh about 9 ounces, <ORGANIZATION> Hanscom </ORGANIZATION> said. The species has a wingspan of up to 10 feet at maturity. The 10-ounce blue-green egg, about 5 inches long, had been under a 24-hour watch since Wednesday, when keepers noticed `` pip'' cracks in one end signaling the start of hatching, which can take three days. After the egg was laid March 3, it was taken away from the parent birds and incubated artificially in hopes that the female bird would produce a second egg. So far, this has not happened. It will be a while before the sex of the bird can be determined through a blood test, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Hanscom </ORGANIZATION> said that representatives of the Chumash Indian tribe had been enlisted to select the name for the chick upon hatching. The tribe inhabited the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> area that most recently served as <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condor habitat, and the bird figures prominently in the tribe's religion.
</TEXT>
