<HEAD>Workers Determined To Win Higher Pay From Government They Don't
Trust</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers glared with icy determination at platoons of plainclothes police as they streamed out through the gates of the huge strike-bound <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> steelworks during a shift change. Striding toward a bus stop, a few flashed the V-for-victory sign once out of sight of police. Their strike at the plant in the <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> has shaken the government at the highest level. At the bus stop 100 yards from the gates, a knot of workers began to talk freely with foreign reporters. `` They have to give people what they deserve,'' A beefy man in a shiny tan jacket said of communist authorities. He punched the air angrily with his finger as he spoke: `` We are working. Prices are going up. We have no money.'' Others murmured agreement and nodded. It was Friday night and workers had occuped the plant for four days, demanding pay raises, the restoration of union rights and reinstatement of dismissed Solidarity activists. A worker on the edge of the group said he made $ 107 a month, half of which he must spend on the maintenance and mortgage on his home: `` We are working all the time, on Sundays too. And we can hardly live.'' Prices have gone up 42 percent so far this year as the result of government reforms aimed at making the economy more market-oriented. `` We do n't believe them anymore,'' a middle-aged man with a quiet manner said of authorities. `` They keep promising -LRB- that things will get better -RRB- and yet we ca n't earn in one day even enough for two kilos -LRB- 4 pounds -RRB- of herring. `` They share millions and we are near starvation.'' The workers have been inside the plant for 16 hours at a stretch during the strike, the nation's worst since martial law stifled the Solidarity independent labor federation 6 -LCB- yearss ago. Strikers spend their day at the plant sitting, talking, tinkering, but not working. They said some workers have not joined the stoppage and toil while their colleagues in a neighboring department sit idle. The strike committee says it represents half the plant's 32,000 workers, and from 12,000 to 14,000 workers are in the plant at any one time.
