<HEAD>Rebels Drop Demand; 11 Arrested In Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebel leaders dropped a demand that their fighters receive ammunition and weapons after moving into cease-fire zones, removing a major obstacle in peace talks with the government. Also Friday, the leftist Sandinista government's labor troubles persisted and police used rubber truncheons to quell protests by striking auto mechanics and construction workers, arresting 11 demonstrators. The decision by leaders of the rebels, known as Contras, not to demand arms supplies after their fighters move into the seven cease-fire zones removed a key barrier to achieving a lasting peace under accords signed March 23. `` We have desisted from receiving replacements of weapons and ammunition in the zones and we accept the concept of sovereignty and indivisibility of national territory,'' top <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leader <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> told a news conference. The Contras had also insisted that the cease-fire zones be autonomous. <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> said, however, that the Contras rejected the government's demand that more than $ 17 million in humanitarian aid to the rebels, recently approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, be channeled through the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> The aid was to be funneled to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> through the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. Under the March 23 agreement signed in the southern border town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, only neutral parties may distribute the aid. The rebels have been supported by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> since 1981, when they mounted the insurgency that has claimed more than 26,000 lives. The Sapoa accords promise them a role in the political process i