<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolodin </PERSON>, one of the first music critics to pay extensive attention to phonograph records, has died after suffering a stroke one year ago. He was 80 years old. <PERSON> Kolodin </PERSON>, who died Friday in a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> nursing home, wrote prolifically about a wide range of musical styles, ranging from classical to jazz. He joined <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> in 1932 and became its chief critic before leaving in 1950. His first book of phonograph record reviews appeared in 1941. Over the course of his career, <PERSON> Kolodin </PERSON> was music critic for The Saturday Review from 1947 to 1982 and historian of the Metropolitan Opera, publishing his first book on the company in 1936. He was working on an edition tracing the first 100 years of the Metropolitan when he suffered a debilitating stroke in 1987. In 1970, <PERSON> Kolodin </PERSON> selected the classical music for the first official White Housw music library. He also taught criticism at the <ORGANIZATION> Juilliard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> from 1968 to 1982. <PERSON> Kolodin </PERSON> was married from 1936 to 1970 to the former <PERSON> Irma </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> and is survived by two stepchildren. Information on funeral arrangements was not immediately available.
