<HEAD>Large Sinkhole Swallows 1 Home, Threatens 2 Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEBRING, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A large sinkhole quickly swallowed a house and two others teetered on the edge in a subdivision near this central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> town, authorities said today. Just two hours after it opened Friday evening, the hole had grown to 70 yards wide and 15 feet deep, witnesses and officials said. No injuries were reported, <LOCATION> Highlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's dispatcher <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON> said `` Every once in a while you can hear a crack'' as it widens, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a 15-year-old who lives a few blocks from the sinkhole. The first home was completely in the hole. The sinkhole also swallowed a garage and was expanding toward two homes next door, Ms. <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON> said. `` The roof's almost even with the road around it,'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>, a geologist in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> who directs the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinkhole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>, said he was surprised to see a large sinkhole in the area. `` We rarely if ever get any that far south,'' he said. Sinkholes are largely caused by the altering of the water table in the limestone and clay under the soil, experts say. A sudden lowering of the water table because of irrigation or drought can weaken and collapse underground limestone caverns, while too much water draining into the ground can dissolve clay-like materials and rock below.
