PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> said. `` I paid for a new chapel in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mateo </LOCATION>, a parish boarding school, and decorations for the church altar, and I helped out the children who needed the money so much. I have n't got a penny of it. `` I repent and I want to die ... I was tempted by Satan and I know the damage I have done to the church and I deserve punishment,'' he said. He said <PERSON> Rojano </PERSON> had pressured him to carry the drugs and that he had asked his church superiors in March to remove him from the parish `` because I was horribly afraid.'' <PERSON> Fathe </PERSON> <PERSON> Amador </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Venezuelan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday that the church is `` disconcerted and full of consternation and pain'' over the case. `` The church does not judge and will let -LRB- Venezuelan -RRB- justice follow its course,'' Merino said. `` In -LRB- <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>'s -RRB- confusion and good faith, I think he believed that this was the best use for the money made from this nefarious trafficking business,'' he said. He said top <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> church officials visited <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> on Thursday `` to be close to him in these moments of confusion.'' He said did n't know of any other cases of Venezuelan church officials involved in drug smuggling. <PERSON> Granadillo </PERSON> said the priest's activities had been under observation for over a year. Police said formal charges wilt be drawn up against the priest and the <PERSON> Rojano </PERSON> couple next week. Drug smuggling in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> carries a jail sentence of six to thirty years, the nation's maximum penalty.
