<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a rare and highly publicized <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> meeting with Russian Orthodox Church leaders, <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> promised greater religious tolerance and sought support for his drive for domestic change. The Soviet leader also condemned past repression of religious activity. He said a law now being drafted on `` freedom of conscience'' will reflect the `` tangible results of new approaches to state-church relations in the conditions of perestroika -LRB- restructuring -RRB- and democratization.'' Friday's meeting was <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s first with high church officials since he became <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief in March 1985. Such a meeting is unusual because party doctrine professes atheism. The encounter, reported by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, was the lead item on the evening news program `` Vremya'' and a front page story in today's editions of Pravda and other Soviet dailies. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said church head Patriarch <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> had requested the meeting with the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief to discuss the June celebration of the 1,000 th anniversary of Christianity's arrival in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said his campaign for the restructuring of society offers benefits to religious believers but also carries obligations that can be met during the 1,000 th anniversary celebration ` On the eve of this event I would like to express the desire that it is marked by the consolidation of our country's believers, all working people, for the sake of our common great cause of perestroika, of the renewal of socialism, complete unfolding of its humanistic ethical potential,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted him as telling the church leaders. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said his overhaul of society and the economy faces opposition at many levels, so the appeal to church leaders was seen as an effort to enlist the support of another element of Soviet society. He did not specify what the new law governing religion would say or when it would be completed, but said it would `` reflect the interests of religious organizations.'' The law now in effect, dating back to 1929, requires registration of all religious groups, and prevents charitable activities and religious education of the young. Archbishop <PERSON> Kiril </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION> told a news conference on March 31 that the rewriting of the law `` will open the possibility for a fuller church life for all believers'' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Under Soviet power, the Russian Orthodox Church has been subject at times to harassment and violent anti-religious campaigns. In 1961, Premier <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> predicted the complete elimination of religion in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> by 1980. <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON>, the 77-year-old patriarch of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and All <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, told <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that Soviet religious leaders `` ardently pray for the success of the restructuring process, and strive to do everything possible for its development,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. However, <PERSON> Pimen </PERSON> said without elaborating that `` not all problems of church life receive their resolution so far.'' In his talk with the prelates, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> acknowledged the suffering of religious believers under the late Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. `` Mistakes made with regard to the church and believers in the 1930s and the years that followed are being rectified,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said, without referring to <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> by name. Religious believers were among the millions of people killed or imprisoned under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. Churches and their property were destroyed during <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s drive to establish collectives. Under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, Soviet media have been reporting extensively on <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s mistakes and repression. The millenium of Russian Christianity has raised the question of a possible visit by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. The Polish-born pontiff, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, has frequently expressed his desire to visit Soviet Catholics, but has publicly disclosed that he has been refused permission at least twice. However, a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> official said on April 20 that changing domestic conditions in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> could pave the way for the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s first Soviet pilgrimage `` I am absolutely sure that this climate -LRB- conducive to a papal visit -RRB- is being created,'' <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Krasikov </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> deputy director general, told a news conference in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>.
