up graf 7 `Morawiecki, who...'
^With PM-Poland, Bjt</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today released two former underground Solidarity leaders from prison in a secret deal with Roman Catholic church officials, but the activists refused to leave the country, family members said. Witnesses and relatives said the two were then returned to a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> prison, but their status remained unclear. A spokesman for the communist government declined comment. The two, <PERSON> Kornel </PERSON> <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON>, were driven to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s airport to board a flight to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, but they decided to stay in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> after meeting with family members. The two were released from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s Rakowiecka prison early today in an apparent deal between the Roman Catholic church and communist authorities. Both men were leaders of a militant Solidarity splinter group. They were given multiple exit-and-entry passports and were supposed to go to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> for unspecified medical treatment. But after meeting with relatives in an airport lounge and hearing of a new wave of strikes, they decided to stay in the country, relatives said. `` They are staying,'' <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Anna </PERSON>, told reporters at the airport. `` They may go at a later date, but they want to think it over.'' <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> were driven back from the airport in two umarked cars. Witnesses who followed said they were returned to <LOCATION> Rakowiecka </LOCATION> prison by security officials. Also present at the airport meeting were three priests from the episcopate and a lawyer. The priests declined to comment. Speaking later to reporters in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>'s daughter said she was surprised that the two men were taken back to prison. `` At first, they agreed to go -LRB- abroad -RRB-. But there was no ultimatum,'' she said. `` They wanted to talk to the families, to consult with each other, because they had no such opportunity in prison.'' She said the two men wanted at least 24 hours to make up their minds. <PERSON> Ewa </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoja </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON>'s girlfriend, said official documents indicated the two men were being released at the recommendation of a commission of prison doctors `` due to the required urgent medical examination, which may also take place abroad.'' The two women said <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> suffered from ulcers and teeth problems, while <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> had ulcer symptoms, poor eyesight, and heart and kidney ailments. <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Morawiecka </PERSON> said the release of the two men was arranged by church officials and that there had been `` some intervention'' by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>, who was was arrested Nov. 9, was chairman of the militant splinter group Fighting Solidarity. He had been in hiding since the December 1981 martial law crackdown on the labor group Solidarity. The next year, he formed Fighting Solidarity, which differs from the outlawed independent labor federation because it advocates anti-communist political goals. Solidarity emphasizes social and union issues. <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> headed Fighting Solidarity from the time of <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>'s arrest until his own capture in January. He had been in hiding since 1985. Authorities alleged that the two were part of a ring that attempted to smuggle equipment intended for terrorist use from <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. They were never formally charged. In a statement in November, <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> denied the allegations. A third, less prominent Fighting Solidarity activist, <PERSON> Krzystof </PERSON> <PERSON> Szymanski </PERSON>, was also released today. In another development, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorny </PERSON>, the Solidarity leader in the southern <LOCATION> Silesian </LOCATION> industrial region, was released after an appeals court on Friday suspended his sentence, Solidarity sources said. <PERSON> Gorny </PERSON> was serving an 18-month sentence at a prison in <LOCATION> Katowice </LOCATION> after being convicted of failing to pay alimony and using false identity cards. In September 1986, the government of Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> issued a broad amnesty for political prisoners. Since then, the political activists it has jailed have been held on criminal charges.
