<DATELINE>TUSKEGEE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge's decision to throw out his temporary restraining order against <ORGANIZATION> Tuskegee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> means students who owe the school more than $ 300 will not be allowed to take final exams next week. <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> had halted the predominantly black private school's crackdown Wednesday. But after a six-hour hearing Friday, <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> dissolved the order. University officials estimate there are 600 students who owe more than $ 300 each, and argued that <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>'s original order had hampered their ability to collect. Students said the crackdown was issued without adequate notice and threatened those students who were having financial difficulties. University President <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Payton </PERSON> said he was `` deeply saddened that it was necessary to go to this length to make that point.'' `` This is not a case of <ORGANIZATION> Tuskegee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> fighting its students,'' he said. `` It's a case of <ORGANIZATION> Tuskegee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> insisting that students learn very important lessons for life.'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> ordered the school to leave its business office open over the weekend so students can make payments before exams begin Monday. The university's crackdown on overdue fees had sparked a week of protests, including a sit-in at the administration building last weekend. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pintard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the ruling was a `` serious miscarriage of justice.'' <PERSON> Pintard </PERSON> said university officials should have identified `` categories of students'' who could n't make payments because of financial difficulties, and worked out a timetable for those students. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said he agreed with the students' complaints on a personal level, adding, `` Prohibiting students from attending class is an exceedingly drastic action, with as little notice as was given.'' But he said he had no legal grounds to stop the school policy because the students did n't show that the university's policy was arbitrary or would irreparably injure them.
