<HEAD>Soviet Buffer Zone Emerging Despite Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY12</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> says it will withdraw <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, but it appears that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is creating a buffer zone along the Soviet border in the northern <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> area. Here is a report from the area.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> MAZAR-E-SHARIF </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ A northern strip of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, rich in agriculture and natural resources, is being transformed into a Soviet buffer zone, despite the planned withdrawal of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops. All nine Afghan provinces bordering the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> recently were grouped to form a new `` Northern Zone'' with a de facto capital in <LOCATION> Mazar-e-Sharif </LOCATION>, ostensibly to coordinate development programs. Virtually isolated from the rest of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by the towering <PERSON> Hindu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kush </PERSON> mountains, the ethnic minorities of the north are closer in language and culture to the Soviets across the border than to their fellow Afghans in the south. `` For several months, there has been an escalation of Sovietization of the north,'' a foreign diplomat in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> said. `` Thousands of young people have gone to school in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Some come home with Russian wives. It's a very classical colonization.'' The diplomat, who spoke on condition he not to be identified further, said the Soviet military withdrawal does not mean the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is abandoning <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> while President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government is still under attack by U.S.-supplied guerrillas `` The Soviets do not want to lose <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The north is a Soviet zone,'' he said. He noted that the `` Northern Zone'' includes <LOCATION> Faryab </LOCATION> province, the Afghan oil region, and said <LOCATION> Faryab </LOCATION> `` is already completely dominated by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' The Soviets have pledged to start withdrawing their 115,000 soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15 under a U.N.-mediated accord signed with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> two weeks ago in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mazar-e-Sharif </LOCATION>, the administrative center of <LOCATION> Balkh </LOCATION> province, sits on a flat plain 40 miles from the <LOCATION> Amu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> that forms the Soviet border. Almost every car in the dusty town is Soviet-made. Shop names are written in the Russian alphabet as well as in the <LOCATION> Arabic-Persian </LOCATION> script used by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Soviet-style posters extolling the virtues of work and socialism loom over the streets. Early this year, references to the new `` Northern Zone'' started appearing in speeches and newspaper articles in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the Afghan capital. `` The main point behind such rearrangement was to coordinate projects and needs, because this area enjoys rich natural resources _ gas, coal, others,'' said <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharif </PERSON>, secretary of the <LOCATION> Balkh </LOCATION> province central committee of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Afghan officials quickly point out that other Afghan provinces also have been grouped into regional zones. But only the `` Northern Zone'' has its own deputy prime minister. <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Masir </PERSON>, minister of mines and industry and former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Afghan-Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Friendship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, was named to the post two months ago. <LOCATION> Mazar-e-Sharif </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, 180 miles south of the border, are expected to be the last cities vacated by Soviet troops before the Feb. 15, 1989, deadline for final withdrawal. According to Afghan and Western observers who spoke on condition of anonymity, <LOCATION> Mazar-e-Sharif </LOCATION> is one of the most pacified areas of the country. In 1987 the official Soviet news media acknowledged that anti-Soviet guerrillas had launched at least two attacks across the border on Soviet soil. According to a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> publication, the Soviets retaliated with attacks that caused `` enormous'' civilian casualties. <PERSON> Sharif </PERSON> said the Soviet-backed Afghan government now controls all but 80 of the 433 villages in <LOCATION> Balkh </LOCATION> province. These figures could not be verified, but 18 months ago Afghan officials said only half the villages were under government control. The nine northern provinces have an estimated 2 million to 3 million inhabitants, about one-fourth of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s total population. Nearly all the people belong to the <LOCATION> Uzbek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kirghiz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tajik </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkmen </LOCATION> tribes _ the same ethnic minorities who live across the border in the Soviet republics of <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kirghizia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tajikistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkmenistan </LOCATION>. Western sources in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> say they strongly doubt the guerrillas, or Islamic holy warriors, can take control of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. But if it does happen, they say the northern zone could serve as a refuge and restaging area for the <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> government. `` If the situation is very bad in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the government could go to the north for reconquest,'' a non-American diplomat said. `` But I should be very surprised if <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> falls. I think <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> will be very well-defended by the Afghan army with Soviet advisers.''
