<SECOND>AM-Question Time, Bjt,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Question-Time: A Twice-Weekly 15-Minute Verbal Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At 3.15 p.m. most Tuesdays and Thursdays, Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> marches into <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> for one of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s liveliest political traditions _ Question Time. Armed with a thick notebook of statistics, she jousts with questioning lawmakers amid the roar of others frantic to make a point. Fifteen minutes later she departs, and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> begins its business for the day. The public gallery is packed for Question Time, and millions more hear the rhetorical fireworks later on radio and TV. Starting this fall, they'll be able to see the action, too, following a Commons decision to let in television cameras. Born in 1721 to allow lawmakers to obtain information, Question Time has developed into a test of ministerial mettle and, some say, a publicity show. In 1901 a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leader called it a `` scandal,'' and today, many say it is more furious than ever. `` It's turned into a kind of gladiatorial battle,'' says <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Beattie </PERSON>, a specialist in Parliament. `` It's very noisy and very crude.'' `` It's become a waste of time,'' says <PERSON> Tam </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalyell </PERSON>, a Laborite expelled from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for five days last year for calling Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> a `` liar'' in Parliament. `` It's hullabaloo.'' The curtain rises on Question Time, a mixture of ancient pomp and modern informality, as 62-year-old Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> takes her seat on the government side of the House. Lawmakers lounging on their green leather pew-like benches sit up, alert. Question from <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>: `` In her endeavor to re-establish the bonds of family life, has the prime minister ever given any consideration to the value of a wife? Is she aware that the <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ... is offering in compensation two pounds -LRB- $ 3.80 -RRB- per week for each keeper's wife? `` Given that the <ORGANIZATION> Forestry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> pays the same keepers 45 pence -LRB- 85 cents -RRB- a week for a ferret and 2.30 pounds -LRB- $ 4.37 -RRB- a week for a dog, should she not intervene?'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> replies: `` I think the honorable gentleman will be aware that the budget set out considerably to help wives ... We on this side value them very highly.'' The sound and fury rises steadily, and by the time Labor leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> begins criticizing Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s welfare reforms, the prime minister's voice is barely audible. She calls <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON>'s remarks `` utterly futile,'' as lawmakers scream `` Answer the Question!,'' `` You're Wrong!'' and Speaker of the House <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Weatherill </PERSON> cries `` Order! Order!'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> relies heavily on statistics for her replies, while some of her predecessors have preferred barbed repartee. The late <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> was once asked: `` Is the prime minister aware of the deep concern felt by the people of this country at the whole question of the Korean conflict?'' To which <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> sniffed: `` I am well aware of the deep concern felt by the honorable member in many matters above his comprehension.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s near-decade in power has led to frustration in opposition ranks, and her personality has caused more friction than perhaps any other <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> leader, <PERSON> Beattie </PERSON> says. `` The strategy she adopts is that you do n't worry if the opposition hates you, you worry about whether your own side thinks you've won,'' says <PERSON> Beattie </PERSON>. Some say speakers tolerate more disorder both in debate and Question Time to ensure the protection of minority party rights, but that tolerance has led to increased unruliness throughout the House. One of the worst recent incidents occurred not during Question Time but at the end of a dramatic debate on taxation. In a show of anti-Thatcher rage, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> hard-liner <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> dropped and dented the gold and silver mace, the club that is a symbol of royal authority in the chamber. He was expelled for 20 working days after refusing to apologize. However, <PERSON> Weatherill </PERSON> says he feels that generally `` the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> proceeds in good order.'' He told the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> he also believes Question Time may quiet down when television enters the chamber for six months this fall. `` I think the new stars are likely to be the reasonable members,'' he said. Opponents argue that TV will encourage showing off. <ORGANIZATION> Strathclyde </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> has offered to teach lawmakers how to perform for television for $ 285 a day but says no one has signed up.
