<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-English     04-30 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-English,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Calls For New Standards For English Teaching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The birthplace of English had better mind its p's and q's and improve its English teaching methods at the same time, according to a government study which criticizes how the language is taught in <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> The study, released Friday by a government-appointed committee, concluded that most English teachers in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> were not properly equipped for the job and recommended that many be retrained. Education Secretary <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> welcomed the report. He said his department will incorporate its recommendations into a new curriculum planned by Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative government in a major shake-up of the nation's educational `` Most schools no longer teach old-fashioned grammar. But little has been put in its place,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said last year when he established the committee to study the situation. The 90-page report follows a yearlong inquiry by the committee into how English is taught in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Panel members include <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Levi </PERSON>, professor of poetry at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>; novelists <PERSON> Antonia </PERSON> <PERSON> Byatt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> Waterhouse; broadcaster <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>; and poet <PERSON> P.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kavanagh </PERSON>. They visited schools across the nation before writing the report. The report says all teachers should be trained in English and that each school should have a teacher whose sole job is to ensure that the language is used properly. It adds that national standards should be established to be met by children at the ages of seven, 11 and 16. However, the committee rejected a return to memorizing grammar rules. `` We're not anxious to go back to the idea that you simply learn these things by rote, because all the evidence is that that does n't in fact improve the effectiveness of the children's use of the language,'' said Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingman </PERSON>, vice-chancellor of <ORGANIZATION> Bristol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and head of the committee <PERSON> Kingman </PERSON> rejected the notion that the new standards would discriminate against pupils from ethnic minority groups. Of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 56 million people, about 2.45 million are non-whites, mostly immigrants from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> whose children were born and raised in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` The fact that they may speak a different language at home is irrelevant, because the English language is the way they become full members of English society,'' <PERSON> Kingman </PERSON> said. `` It is a way of ensuring that we do not have an underclass of non-English speakers who are cut off from getting a job and having a career.'' The opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the 184,400-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> also welcomed the report. But <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Inner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>'s English Center, said he was concerned about the notion that all pupils must conform to a standard form of English. `` About 80 percent of pupils do not speak standard English although they speak something very close to it. Any attempt to get kids to speak standard English will just disable them as speakers,'' he said. <LOCATION> Kingman </LOCATION>, a mathematician, said English teachers were not being trained well in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and that children were suffering. `` We take a fairly dim view of English teacher training,'' he said. The report said that by age 7, children should read passages of simple sentences, understand the spoken language, spell common words and write legibly; by 11, they should use punctuation and paragraphs, argue their case on an issue and be aware of dialects. It said 16-year-olds should be able to express feelings, ideas and arguments in writing and speech, make comparisions between English and other languages and use technical terms to describe language. English is the first language of 320 million people around the world and is spoken daily by about a billion people.
