 A college professor who once claimed to operate the `` cleanest massage parlor in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'' has been charged with conspiracy to maintain a house of prostitution, law enforcement officials said. <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON>, chairman of the business department at <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, is to be arraigned Thursday on the prostitution charge and two counts of income tax evasion, according to Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Eldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>. The tax charges accuse <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON> of failing to file a return with the state <ORGANIZATION> Franchise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> for 1985 and 1986. Financial records seized at his home in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marino </LOCATION> indicate he earned at least $ 200,000 each of those years, <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said Friday. <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Glassman </PERSON>, said his client would plead innocent to the conspiracy charge. `` <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> may have been lax, he may have been negligent in some things, but he did n't know what was going on at the massage parlor,'' <PERSON> Glassman </PERSON> said. The attorney said that while <PERSON> Mintz </PERSON> had not filed state tax returns for 1985 and 1986, he was in the process of doing so when his records were seized. The <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> Massage Parlor, located across the street from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>, adjacent to upscale <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, was closed in February after authorities said it was being used as a house of prostitution. Six former employees of the ma