<FIRST>r p AM-HowDukakisDidIt Bjt   04-30 1213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-How Dukakis Did It, Bjt,1190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis' Early Success At Fund Raising Helped Later Victories At
Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Neither <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> nor his friend and money-raiser <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> assumed great success when they sat down at the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor's breakfast table one day in the fall of 1986. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was casting an eye toward the presidency, and he had one question. `` He said, ` Look, if I decide to go for this thing, will the money be there to wage a credible campaign?''' Farmer recalled. Farmer responded with some optimism, but a day later he had second thoughts. He called <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` I'm troubled by one thing,'' he told <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` I've never raised money for a guy who's at 1 percent in the polls.'' As it turned out, <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> underestimated. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has been underestimated all along in this presidential campaign, much as his fall opponent, Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has been. Critics fault <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for a cold aloofness, a lack of passion, and a presence that creates barely a ripple outside a staged event. Not until <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s primary Tuesday, where he won by 2-to-1 over <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, did polls show that as many as half those who voted for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> actually supported him strongly. `` This guy really is the <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Dangerfield </PERSON> of presidential politics,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckel </PERSON>, who managed <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>'s 1984 campaign. `` This guy gets more criticism for a winner than anybody I've seen in modern presidential politics.'' `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is a man who is easy to underestimate,'' says his friend, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>. `` But he is extremely competent and well disciplined and has good values _ and all that comes through to the voters.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had other advantages, aside from money. He was helped by geography and a primary calender that fit nicely with his bases of support. And like any winner he was lucky. He was a beneficiary of <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>'s political self-immolation, the disasters and missteps that befell other opponents, the reluctance of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> to enter the race, and the lack of national stature of his opponents. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> announced his candidacy on April 29, 1987 with a direct shot at the then front-runner <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> and his campaign of `` new ideas.'' `` Ask more than whether we have new ideas,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` Ask whether we have already made new ideas work.'' He called himself a long-shot when he entered the race. But within a month all that was altered by the revelations of <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>'s relationship with a young woman `` I do n't think you have any real sense at the time you make that kind of announcement what's likely to happen,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I said at the time it's a very, very long shot. I meant it. We're all long shots. I mean, who knows? It's a very unpredictable business. `` I thought that if we could organize well and raise sufficient funds and really work at it _ as I always have _ there was a possibility that we could do it. It's never more than a possibility when you start.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> sustained his theme for a year: never mind the charisma, here was a politician who had made government work. He offered as evidence the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> economic turnaround, notwithstanding critics who said he did no more than stay out of the way of a boom that was coming anyway. `` I do n't think people are all that naive _ I do n't think anybody really thought he created the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Miracle out of whole cloth,'' said <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>. `` But they knew that he'd been a part of it and that he'd seen the future they wanted to achieve.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaigned in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> with the knowledge that he had a sure win a week later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, his neighboring state. He campaigned in the South, potentially hostile territory, by leaving Dixie to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and concentrating on atypical Southern voters: Jews and retirees in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, Hispanics in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, liberals throughout the region. He was credited with a strong organization and was able to withstand the loss of his campaign manager and top aide, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>, in the flap over <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>'s role in campaign sabotage that revealed Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s plagiarism and lapses of judgment. He was also lucky that his third place showing in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> was n't viewed as the setback it might have been <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign chairman and longtime friend <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said his <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> finish was `` perceived as a strong showing.'' `` Part of the plan was to do well enough in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> so you could preserve the geographic advantage you have in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Had he not done well in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, his support in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> may have softened.'' Critics and supporters will argue over whether <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s belated emergence was a triumph of money over message, but it is indisputable that his financial success made much of it possible. Farmer, who had been treasurer for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> in 1984, initially thought he could raise $ 6.5 million by the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses in early February. His figure was in line with what the wealthiest of the other Democrats were able to raise. But the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign raised $ 17 million by <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s caucus night _ a financial triumph that gave <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> an enormous advantage over his rivals and paved the way for his emergence as the likely Democratic presidential nominee. His bankroll allowed him to run campaigns everywhere, and to keep staff in place while opponents were collapsing their efforts into <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. He was prepared, as a result, when the campaign moved into the foreign territory of the South and he was able to survive consecutive losses in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. He headed North after Super Tuesday with $ 2 million in the bank, while his opponents were broke or in debt. How was <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> able to do it and not the others? One reason was the network Farmer built, asking not just for contributions but for each significant donor to produce $ 10,000 in contributions from their friends. He got enthusiastic support from Greek-Americans around the country, tapping an igorned but often affluent community that contributed close to one-fifth of his total. Importantly, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s own state had a booming economy and active Democrats accustomed to giving. The race for money, in fact, can be considered one of the major contests of 1988. And <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won it going away. `` It is n't that candidates lose heart, it's that they run out of money,'' <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said. `` Money is the winnowing factor in this process.'' Former rivals and current supporters alike say the critics of his dispassionate style have missed something that voters found in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s cool temperament. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON>, polltaker for <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, said research done for that campaign found a startlingly positive reaction among voters to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on television, particularly in his commercials. He communicated, <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON> said, `` an inner strength, a quiet passion, an intelligent commitment to substance.'' `` That is not the typical interpretation that's put on the guy, but I'm convinced of it from research that we have done,'' <PERSON> Mellman </PERSON> said. `` Not sort of rip-roaring, table-thumping passion, but deep concern and deep conviction. That speaks well of him. That establishes a bond of trust with the voter.''
