<HEAD>Water Rationing Begins Sunday, But Allottments Delayed For Two
Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Water rationing begins Sunday, but city residents wo n't discover how much water they will be allotted for another two weeks. Beginning May 15, customers will receive notices telling them how much water they can use, the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. `` We are asking people to wait until they get their allotment before they start saying they wo n't have enough water. They should wait until they know,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>, general manager at the <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` I would encourage them to start saving water now and not panic until they see how much they will get,'' <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON> said. Reduced rain and snow has lowered reservoirs from northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The rationing program, adopted Thursday by the city's <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, is aimed at reducing consumption by 25 percent compared with 1987. Among other things, the new rules prohibit washing sidewalks, operating decorative fountains and serving water to restaurant patrons except on request. The rationing program will depend on public cooperation, and the only penalities will be increased rates for excessive use and possible installation of flow restrictors for big wasters, said <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>.
