<FIRST>r p AM-PresidentialEconomy Bjt   04-30 0818</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Presidential Economy, Bjt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy Friendly To Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s viewpoint, the American economy could n't be friendlier: consumer spending is booming, unemployment falling and the prospects of inflation too ethereal to stir much worry. In fact, the economy's prospects appear so bright that one leading economic forecasting firm has an economic model showing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will win the presidency on Nov. 8 with 53 percent of the vote. That forecast by <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> uses a computer model which combines what is already known about the economy's performance over the past six months with the firm's expectations for growth and inflation between now and election day. Using an economic model to forecast an election still six months may be going out on a limb, but economists said the exercise does highlight the importance economic issues play in voters' decisions. `` The model has been correct in the past. People do vote their pocketbooks,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, chief financial economist at <ORGANIZATION> DRI </ORGANIZATION>. `` When things are going well, they want more of the same and that is what Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is promising.'' At the start of the year, things did not look as promising for the Republicans. The 508-point stock market plunge on Oct. 19 had spawned widespread fears that the country would fall into a recession in the early part of 1988. In the three months following the collapse, consumer spending fell by the biggest amount since 1980 when <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> was president. Consumer spending accounts for two-thrids of overall economic activity, and that decline toppled the country into a brief recession which is cited as one of the factors leading to <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s re-election defeat. But this time around, the economy kept rolling. The government reported last Tuesday that consumer spending, propelled by strong auto sales, rebounded nicely in the first three months of the year, providing the momentum for 2.3 percent growth in the overall economy, as measured by the gross national product. The economic expansion, which has now lasted for a peacetime record of 64 months, has driven the unemployment rate down to a nine-year low of 5.6 percent. The unexpectedly strong growth this year and the big gains in employment are raising some concerns that inflation is about to become a problem again. Economists are worried that with job markets growing tight and many industries operating at high capacity rates, demand will start to push prices higher. Prices at both the retail and wholesale levels took a big jump up in March, raising fears in financial markets that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> will be forced to step in with a dose of higher interest rates aimed at cooling off demand. Some analysts believe the central bank has already tightened slightly and they predict interest rates will be pushed up another notch if next Friday's unemployment report shows the jobless rate dipped further to 5.5 percent in April. But many analysts believe the increases in inflation and interest rates likely to occur over the next six months will be so small that they wo n't prove worrisome to voters. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Straszheim </PERSON>, chief economist at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>, predicted that interest rates will only increase by one-half to one full percentage point and this will not be enough to curb what he expects will be generally good economic growth this year. `` If the economy does as well as expected between now and November that should be awfully good news for the Republicans because presidents get the credit or the blame for the economy's performance whether they deserve it or not,'' <PERSON> Straszheim </PERSON> said The Democrats can be expected to try to focus the campaign on such problems as the huge budget and trade deficits and the unease Americans feel about the country's slide in the past eight years into the status of the world's leading debtor nation. `` Questions about whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be able to compete in the future and what Americans' living standards will be should affect the outcome as well,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, another economist forecasting firm. But other analysts said these issues remain distant abstractions when compared to such pocket-book matters as jobs and inflation. Analysts also said that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s exceptional luck with the economy appears to be rubbing off on his vice president. While the country had to endure the steepest recession since the Depression in 1981-82, the recovery was well underway by the time <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had to run for re-election. Many economists are predicting the next downturn will begin in 1989, leaving plenty of time for the recovery to start before the next presidential election. `` It is almost magical the way the economy has performed the right way for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at just the right time,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is a lucky man to be second in line to the luck of the Irish.''
