<HEAD>Cuba Builds Up Angola Forces, US Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has quietly expanded its troop commitment to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> by up to 10,000 over the past five months while taking an increasingly active role in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> peace negotiations, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The officials made the disclosure as <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, along with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, prepared for a new round of talks on an array of southern African issues. The talks, scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, mark the first time that South African and Angolan representatives have agreed to sit at the same negotiating table to discuss a peace settlement. The two countries have been military rivals for more than a decade. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> had not taken a direct part in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> peace negotiations until January when <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> officials joined Angolan negotiators for talks with a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> delegation in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, who asked not to be identified, said that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is believed to have had between 35,000 and 37,000 troops in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> as of last November. Since then 8,000 to 10,000 Cuban troops have been sent to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, bringing the total to between 43,000 and 45,000, the officials said. This is believed to be the largest number of Cuban troops deployed in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> since they were first sent there in 1975 when <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> won its independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. If the Cuban and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> populations are compared, the current <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troop commitment in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> is proportionally far greater than the American military involvement in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in 1968 when 525,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen _ the all-time high _ were stationed there. Since early March, about 5,000 Cuban troops have been sent to the western Angolan city of <LOCATION> Benguela </LOCATION>, the officials said. The area is not close to any combat zones in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s motives for the buildup are not clear. The Cubans generally have stayed away from combat zones in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s civil war but a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> defector, <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Pino </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, has said that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has suffered about 10,000 casualties since 1975. Cuban troops were initially sent to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> that year to protect the country's Marxist government against attacks from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Recently, South African forces have been assisting the U.S.-backed <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebel group in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. This is one of the issues delegates from the four countries will discuss at this week's meetings in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> is eager for an end to the South African presence as well as a suspension of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. The highest priority for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is an agreement for the early withdrawal of Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said that once that hurdle is cleared, it will implement a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for independence and black majority rule in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s southern neighbor which has been ruled by <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> since early in the century. However, there has been no agreement on a timetable for the mutual withdrawal of foreign forces from both <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. The head of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> delegation at <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> will be Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, who has been attempting since 1981 to negotiate both Namibian independence and a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>.
