<HEAD>Striking Seamen Fight on Thatcher's Battleground</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of pickets who massed behind police lines as two strikebreaking ferries sailed into <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> on Saturday are on the front line in a battle against Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s labor policies. Like other unions that mounted major strikes in recent years _ steelworkers, coal miners and newspaper printers _ the seamen milling on the dockside of this English Channel port say they are fighting for survival. `` You can take our money, but you ca n't take our minds, you ca n't take our hearts,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> McCluskie </PERSON>, leader of the 24,400-strong <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seamen </ORGANIZATION>, whose three-month strike has crippled P and <ORGANIZATION> O </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferries </ORGANIZATION>' cross-channel fleet. `` We will stand together.'' The rhetoric has the ring of yesteryear's battles to save jobs and retain restrictive work practices that critics say slowed <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s economic recovery. Even as the pickets cheered <PERSON> McCluskie </PERSON>'s call for unity, P and O's strikebreaking ferries, Pride of <LOCATION> Bruges </LOCATION> and Pride of <LOCATION> Kent </LOCATION>, were steaming toward <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION>. Their crews were drawn from the 1,100 P and O ferry workers who have returned to work on company terms. The pickets are among 720 refusing to go along with P and O's plans to trim its staff and impose longer working hours. P and O has fired the strikers. The company's main rival, <ORGANIZATION> Sealink </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferries </ORGANIZATION>, is trying to keep its fleet in operation by invoking union-curbing legislation passed since Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> came to power in 1979. Sealink has asked a court to seize the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seamen </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 5.3 million in assets under a 1984 law barring sympathy strikes. But the company has moved hesitantly because it does not want to trigger a nationwide strike. Sealink's nervousness and a series of delays by P and O before the strikebreaking ferries slipped their moorings showed that the union still has clout. Moreover, ships' officers are wary of sailing with non-union crews, and picket lines discourage potential ferry passengers. The Conservative government's law that makes unions liable for damages over sympathy strikes is the one that helped crack prolonged and often violent stoppages by newspaper production unions and coal miners. P and O Chairman Sir <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> says the company must slim down and relax work practices or be killed by competition from the Channel Tunnel between <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, scheduled to open in 1993. <PERSON> McCluskie </PERSON> and his strikers also see the battle in apocalyptic terms. `` When I joined the Queen <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> as a cabin boy, I thought I had a job for life,'' said a 38-year-old seaman who identified himself only as <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> for fear of losing his job. `` If we lose this,'' he said, `` that's the end of jobs for British seamen.'' For the seamen's union, the strike is the bitter fruit of industrial decline. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s once-mighty shipbuilding industry has collapsed, and many British shipowners have switched to flags of convenience and hired foreign crews to cut labor costs, as have shipowners in other industrialized countries. Its membership having fallen from 150,000 in the 1950s to below 25,000 today, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seamen </ORGANIZATION> sees the cross-channel ferries as its lifeblood.
