<HEAD>Marino Returns To The South As First Black American Archbishop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bishop <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>, about to become the first black archbishop of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, returns this week to a South he believes has `` come of age'' since he left his native <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> 36 years ago bearing childhood wounds of racial prejudice. The 53-year-old <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>, an auxiliary bishop in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, archdiocese since 1974, will be installed Thursday as archbishop of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, taking charge of a 69-county region of northern <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> recalls a childhood in <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, in which, for example, he and his sister were kicked out of a coin-operated laundry because they were black. But he said in a recent interview feels `` personally very comfortable'' about returning to the South. `` I think that the South has changed and come of age and grown,'' he said. `` In many ways, the race question has been more effectively addressed in much of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> than it has been in the North. `` I think I will be able as a black person to function better in a Southern situation, as a Southerner, than I might be able to function in some Northern situation,'' he said. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>'s appointment by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in March came more than two years after he and other black bishops wrote a pastoral letter calling on the church to increase the number of blacks in official positions. One of only 12 black bishops in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> became the first to hold an office in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> when he was elected secretary of the organization in 1985. But despite his role as a trailblazer for blacks in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> church, and despite <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s long tradition in the civil rights movement, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said he does not necessarily see himself becoming a leader in that struggle. `` I certainly am open to any position that presents itself to me,'' he said. `` But I do n't think leaders go out and become leaders. I think the situation and the need on one hand, and opportunities and character and ability on the other, come together and that's what produces a leader.'' Still, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said he's `` delighted and honored and thrilled'' to be moving to a city `` with a magnificant legacy and such a beautiful tradition of leadership in this movement.'' <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> will succeed Archbishop <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnellan </PERSON>, who died Oct. 15. He said he plans to spend his first year traveling around the 21,445 square miles of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> archdiocese, which has a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> population of 156,000 out of a total population of 3.7 million. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said Catholics in the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> archdiocese should not expect `` anything tremendously new or different'' under his leadership. He said his most immediate goal will be to identify the poor in the area and `` call the people of the church to a greater awareness of the presence of the poor.'' As the sixth of eight children growing up in a traditional Catholic family, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> attended elementary and high school at Our Mother of Sorrows Parish in <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION> and decided at an early age to become a priest. In 1952, at age 18, he entered the <ORGANIZATION> Josephites </ORGANIZATION>, an order founded in 1893 to minister to blacks. After four years at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, he completed his studies for the priesthood at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and was ordained a priest in 1962 He taught science and religion at the minor seminary in <LOCATION> Newburgh </LOCATION>, then received his Master of Arts degree in religious education from <ORGANIZATION> Fordham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1967. He was named spiritual director of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 1968 and three years later was elected vicar general of the <ORGANIZATION> Josephites </ORGANIZATION>. During his 14 years as an auxiliary biship in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> was known as an advocate for the poor, the imprisoned and the homeless, frequently serving as their spokesmen before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think that one of the principal demands that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> places on the church and upon those who are the ministers of the churches is to reach out to the poor and the homeless, to those who are without shelter,'' he said. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said he also intends to bring the message that `` we must be a welcoming church, we must be an evangelizing church,'' particularly to blacks who make up less than 3 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are not looking to draw people away from their own churches,'' he said, `` but we certainly want to invite people who have no religious affiliation to come and see what it is that we have.''
