<HEAD>End Material Embargoed for 1:06 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The 1,000-page bill, fashioned over three years of congressional debate, won 63-36 approval Thursday in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ three votes short of the margin needed to overturn a presidential veto. Because of the measure's length, clerical work and printing are expected to delay its delivery to the president until midweek at the earliest. The bill would overhaul the nation's system for imposing import curbs to retaliate against international trade violations and aid American industries threatened by stepped-up foreign competition. An section added to the bill requires all but the smallest employers to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. There are exceptions for companies that find themselves in serious financial trouble. The administration opposes the provision, saying it does not belong in the trade bill and would cramp <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic growth and encourage companies to locate elsewhere by adding new federal regulation. Supporters argue that the idea is humane and decent. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a senior administration official said Friday that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto message is expected to cover at least plant closings and the bill's curbs on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil exports. `` It wo n't be a laundry list of items but we want to give <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> a clear idea of what the president will accept in a second bill,'' the official said. He said Cabinet officers were being consulted about their objections.
