<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> finished last in all nine triathlons he entered last year, but he says he was the winner. Just living is a victory for the 49-year-old heart-transplant recipient. `` I used to live for the bonus check at the end of each month,'' said the former <LOCATION> Tuscon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, insurance executive who will compete here Sunday in a triathlon. `` Now, the way I look at it, every day is a bonus check. `` I'm not out there to win any race. But I feel that every race I'm in I win,'' he said. As a successful executive, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> worked 16 hours a day, smoked heavily and never exercised. But that changed when he received a heart transplant in 1985 after a yearlong bout with heart disease. He started walking, and four months later entered a five-kilometer walkathon. Six weeks after that, he entered a 10-kilometer race, walking much of the way and finishing dead last. Triathlons _ races that combine running, swimming and bicycling _ were his next step. He started training and in April 1986 entered one in <LOCATION> Tuscon </LOCATION>. `` People were saying, ` Hurry up, hurry up!' and I was like ` I'm moving That's fast enough.' I was like the clown in the rodeo,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. As he trained for the Sunday event, he recalled a race in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> last year. While awaiting the start, he spotted <PERSON> Herschel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Tweed </PERSON>, parents of the teen-ager whose heart he received. `` I walked over and they all gave me a hug,'' said <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. `` Then just before the race they were yelling, ` Go get'em, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>!' I was actually crying, standing there before the start of the race.''
