<FILEID>AP-NR-04-30-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-DemocraticText     04-30 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Democratic Text,710</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response given Saturday by Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s radio address: President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ought to sign the trade bill He will make a foolish mistake if he vetoes the bill. It will be a foolish mistake because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is on the threshold of a new economic era. To preserve our standard of living in the 1990s, we must do better, much better, in the game of global trade. The American people understand this. That's why the trade bill passed the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by a large bipartisan majority. The bill recognizes that we need to do two things above all: we must launch an export campaign unprecedented in our history; and we must improve our productivity. The bill plots a strategy for increasing exports. First, it liberates firms from the red tape of unduly tight export controls. Second, it boosts export promotion efforts to benefit American companies. Third, it blows the whistle on unequal and unfair trade. Many countries have gotten rich off of free access to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market while protecting their home markets. These countries can now afford to eliminate their trade barriers. The bill requires them to live up to their international obligations _ pure and simple. We seek a level playing field. But it takes more than a level playing field to compete. You've got to have skilled employees And a sure way to boost labor productivity is to strengthen education and training. The trade bill would entitle all workers who lose their jobs to imports to training or remedial education. It provides nearly a billion dollars for the readjustment of other workers. And it renews the nation's commitment to math, science, foreign language and vocational education. In addition, the bill requires large, financially sound companies to give their employees and communities 60 days notice of plant closings or mass layoffs. It merely calls for a measure of common courtesy on the part of those companies that can afford it. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> get 60 days notice when they lose their job; so does the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Why should n't ordinary citizens? Even President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s own task force and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> say that advance notice is good business practice. The president objects because he believes this is a matter for the private sector, not the government, to decide. Well, Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, the private sector has had every opportunity to take care of this problem on its own terms; it has failed. One-third of all workers get no notice; they're told to pick up their paychecks and leave. Two-thirds of all workers get less than two weeks' notice. They may have put in 20 years of service and have two kids in college, but they're out of the street _ just like that. Years ago, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people decided that it makes sense to ease the social and economic costs of unrestrained free enterprise. We enacted child labor, minimum wage and antitrust laws. The plant closing provision is squarely in this tradition. Critics say the provision has nothing to do with competitveness. They're wrong. If a worker had advance notice of a layoff, he has time to make arrangements for retraining before the clock starts ticking on his unemployment insurance. Reducing the period of unemployment; facilitating retraining; that is what improving labor productivity is all about. Today, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> needs a workforce that is flexible and adaptable, able to shift rapidly to changing economic conditions. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> have already figured this out; they have advance-notice requirements. To oppose this provision is to resist an effort to move this country into the 1990s. It is tragic that the president is threatening to kill the entire bipartisan trade bill on account of this one provision. In truth, his opposition is really based on symbolism; he fears a symbolic victory for labor. Is mere symbolism worth the price of needlessly unemployed people and depressed communities? Is it worth the price of another several years without a coherent foreign economic policy? Is it worth killing a bipartisan bill which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> spent three years on? Common sense says no. Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, the country is ready for the 1990s. For the sake of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people, sign the trade bill.
</TEXT>
