<BYLINE>By NABILA MEGALLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The decision to widen the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military role in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> could make the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the policeman of the waterway, despite its aversion to the task, gulf shipping officials said Saturday. The shipping community generally welcomed President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s decision to expand its protection of foreign vessels from attacks by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> But some shippers also complained that the new policy does not go far enough. `` The best attitude to adopt now is a wait-and-see one,'' said a shipping executive who has complained that his vessels, mainly flying <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> flags, were left at the mercy of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> as the big powers protected their own shipping. `` From what has been annnounced, protection has not been guaranteed for all ships,'' he said. `` It sounds like an elastic policy that will be used by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the right moment, when they choose to take on the Iranians.'' Under the policy announced Friday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces will go to the aid of non-communist, neutral ships that ask for help after being fired upon. Previously, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships protected only those ships reflagged with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flags or registered as U.S.-flagged vessels, including 11 Kuwaiti oil tankers. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> escorts through the gulf, however, frequently have picked up `` hitchhiker'' vessels that are not <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flagged. `` In effect, -LRB- the new policy -RRB- could turn out to be a substitute for the proposal to have a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> naval task force protect shipping in the gulf until the Iraq-Iran war ends,'' said another gulf shipping executive. `` And despite statements by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is going to find itself becoming the policeman in the waterway.'' He was referring to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s comment that despite the policy change, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was not the `` policemen of the gulf, nor do we wish to be. Said another executive: `` I think the Americans are taking on a tremendous load ... doing the job the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> is supposed to do.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s state-run radio said Saturday that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s decision proved the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was backing <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the 7 -LCB- - year-old war The radio said that by protecting neutral vessels, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be `` seeking to limit the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s retaliatory powers. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> attacks neutral vessels in retaliation for <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> strikes on Iranian oil installations and tankers. In the past year, 46 Americans have been killed in or near the gulf, including two <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> pilots who disappeared with their aircraft April 18 after reporting hostile radar locked on their helicopter. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claimed the aircraft was shot down. The biggest loss of American life occurred May 17 in an accidental Iraqi missile strike on the frigate Stark. Thirty-seven <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sailors died. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has sought a multinational naval escort force in the gulf under the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> flag. Less than 10 percent of the ships sailing gulf waters fly communist-bloc flags The gulf supplies nearly 20 percent of the non-communist world's petroleum and is the major trading route for the coastal states that depend on imports for most of their food and commodity supplies The spread of hostilities into the gulf from the Iraq-Iran war has harmed port trade and tended to reduce ship traffic in the waterway. Still, an average of 20 tankers and freighters a day make their way in and out of the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, the entry to the gulf. On Saturday, the 27th convoy this year of reflagged Kuwaiti ships headed out of the gulf escorted by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military spokesman said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, British, French, Italian and Soviet warships escorting their commercial vessels became routine last year when the Iranians stepped up their attacks on commercial shipping with gunboat attacks and the laying of mines. None of the shipping executives who commented on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy change would be quoted by name. Many of the officials do business with both <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Some shipping executives said they believed <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would find ways to continue menacing ships despite the expanded <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> role. `` Who's to prevent the Iranians sowing hundreds of mines in the waterway? They manufacture them,'' said one. `` Who's to prevent them firing Silkworm anti-ship missiles at a convoy moving through the Hormuz? `` They will be ready to take in stride the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> taking on all their missile batteries there. In the end, it's the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that will be the loser, finding itself in a state of war.''
