<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A French patrol boat opened fire on Melanesian separatists Saturday in the navy's first direct role in violence that has left seven people dead on this island territory. Twenty-one French police officers were still held hostage in caves on the New Caledonian island of <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION>. An opposition spokesman demanded that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> agree to a referendum on independence. In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, the main separatist movement accused the French government of waging a `` colonial war'' against the native Melanesians. About 25 military policemen traded gunfire with about 30 armed rebels near a guerrilla encampment at <LOCATION> Pouebo </LOCATION>, a village on the island's east coast, said <PERSON> Philippe </PERSON> <PERSON> Berges </PERSON>, chief of staff at the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> office here. A patrol boat just off the coast fired submachine guns at the insurgents, he said. No injuries were reported on either side. But the exchange was indicative of the rapidly escalating proportions of the conflict. Asked if the insurgency had reached civil war stage, <PERSON> Berges </PERSON> said: `` It's beginning to look that way.'' The main separatist group, the <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> that the navy detroyed a fishermen's cooperative in <LOCATION> Pouebo </LOCATION>. It charged that the French army was stepping up its operations throughout the territory. `` Faced with this situation of colonial war, the <LOCATION> Kanak </LOCATION> people are organizing to thwart the occupation forces,'' the statement said. Front spokesman <PERSON> Leopold </PERSON> <PERSON> Joredie </PERSON> said Saturday that the group wants a mediator appointed to negotiate terms of an island-wide referendum on self-rule. He said a mediator must be named before the insurgents will respond to President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s appeal for the immediate release of the hostages. The violence began April 22 when separatists tried to block French presidential elections scheduled on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> on April 24. Rebels raided a police station, kidnapping 27 gendarmes and killing four others. Twelve hostages were subsequently released. But eight more lawmen were seized Wednesday when they tried to negotiate the release of the remaining hostages. Two of those hostages, the head of an anti-terrorism squad and an assistant prosecutor, were subsequently released and ordered to negotiate on behalf of the terrorists. They were told the remaining hostages would be killed if the two men did not return to the rebel hideout. Because of that threat, the government said it considers the two to still be hostages. The native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, make up 43 percent of the territory's 145,000 people. About 36 percent of the population is <LOCATION> European </LOCATION>, with the rest primarily Asian or Tahitian.
