<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of the country's main guerrilla movement, the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, are reeling from a string of setbacks, including revelations of a spy in their midst and a crackdown on anti-apartheid groups. Three guerrillas face a possible trip to the gallows, one leader was assassinated and a purported informer supposedly photographed secret guerrilla documents and turned them over to the government. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leaders acknowledge the setbacks and have acknowledged that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s nearly 2-year-old state of emergency has hobbled <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> efforts to undermine white-minority rule. During a recent trip to <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, guerrilla leaders engaged in `` an orgy of self-criticism,'' according to a story last week in The Weekly Mail, an anti-apartheid newspaper. But it said there remained lingering optimism. `` The emergency and the general repression are counterproductive for the regime,'' <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Tshwete </PERSON> was quoted as saying. `` In terms of heightening resentment and mobilizing mass opinion... the situation is favorable for our activities. But the bad news for the congress includes: _ The March 29 assassination of guerrilla leader <PERSON> Dulcie </PERSON> September in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. _ The April 7 maiming of <PERSON> Albie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, a lawyer and <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> member who was seriously injured by a car bomb in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. _ The April 15 death of a guerrilla killed when a mine he was carrying blew up in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, prompting pro-government newspapers to claim the group has stooped to using poorly trained `` kamikaze'' bombers. In February, the government prohibited political activities by major anti-apartheid groups. In addition, three <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members convicted of murder, terror and treason face possible death sentences. In <LOCATION> Messina </LOCATION>, near the northern border with <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mzondileli </PERSON> <PERSON> Nondula </PERSON>, 25, and <PERSON> Mthetheleli </PERSON> <PERSON> Mncube </PERSON>, 28, are expected to be sentenced within the next few days. <PERSON> Nondula </PERSON> was convicted of killing two white women and four children who died in a blast when the truck they were riding in struck a mine. <PERSON> Mncube </PERSON> was convicted of planting a mine that killed a black man in November 1985 and of killing two white policemen during a subsequent escape attempt. In the southeastern city of <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>, 24, was convicted of carrying out several bombings, including one that killed a police colonel. At another trial of three alleged <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members charged with terrorism and treason, evidence submitted included secret internal documents, purportedly photographed by a spy, that cited problems faced by the guerrilla movement because of informers and shortages of weapons and funds. Defense witnesses described <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> as a gentle young man who joined the congress in a state of despair over racial discrimination in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where the system of apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. Taking the stand to plead for his life, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> professed loyalty to the congress but voiced some disenchantment. Asked what he would do if he could start over again, he replied: `` I would like to be a teacher.'' Formed as a non-violent civil rights group in 1912, the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> was banned in 1960 and a year later began a bombing and sabotage campaign. Its tactics are repudiated by some moderate blacks, but it is believed capable of winning a national election if restrictions on black voting rights and political activity were lifted.
