<HEAD>Students, Townspeople Enjoy Spectacle of First Prom Since 1962</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM PARSONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORREST CITY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The gawkers began gathering more than an hour before the 9 p.m. start of the first <LOCATION> Forrest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> High School Senior Prom in more than a quarter-century. They sat in pickup trucks and cars in the parking lot of the Civic Center; others cruised the lot, eyeing the front door. Some may have been drawn by the mobile van of a <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> television station, its satellite transmission dish aimed skyward. Mostly, they were curious. It was the first integrated Senior Prom for the school. The last Senior Prom was held in 1962 and blacks did not begin attending <LOCATION> Forrest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> High until 1965. A group of black junior high youngsters gathered near the entrance, waiting to see what their older friends and relatives looked like in their tuxedos and formals _ some bought, some made and some rented. `` We'll be going to the Junior Prom'' in May, said <PERSON> Ora </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamerson </PERSON>, 14, from amid a group of four young girls. In the meantime, she was enjoying the spectacle, calling out to her older friends, waving, admiring their togs. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON>, 18, among the older, white onlookers, was n't dressed for the prom. She dropped out of school in January. `` I do n't think it'll work out,'' she said. `` There's a lot of racial problems in <LOCATION> Forrest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. I just do n't think it'll work out.'' But police, who were on hand to enforce the school administration's strict no-cigarettes, no-alcohol, no-drug policy, said the celebration proceeded without incident. `` Everything stayed quiet,'' Police Sgt. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said at 2 a.m. Saturday. Outside the Civic Center, as the prom got under way, there were a few good-natured jeers at unfamiliar finery _ no catcalls or taunts, racial or otherwise. <PERSON> Tangella </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 17, <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> president, said just having it all finally come together, after months of planning, was perhaps the most important thing for her. The final day's preparations and decorations took so long that she was 45 minutes late herself. Earlier in the week, she said the prom owed its existence to the enthusiasm of her classmates, who number about 350. `` Each class has their own thoughts about things, each class thinks they're better,'' she said. `` We felt like we would have a prom, and we did.''
