<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palestinian youths pelted troops with stones Saturday in scattered anti-Israeli protests in the occupied territories, and four Palestinians and a soldier were injured, military and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> sources said. The occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> were relatively quiet after one of the calmest weeks since a Palestinian uprising began December 8. Israeli officials, encouraged by the relative calm, have claimed that the protests are fading. In the main marketplace of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, the largest city in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> youths attacked <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops with stones, according to an army representative who spoke on condition of anonymity. The troops opened fire and wounded a protester, he said. Arab reporters in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> said a second protester was wounded. In the nearby <LOCATION> Balata </LOCATION> refugee camp, young Palestinians hurled stones at <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops, injuring one, the spokesman said. Troops wounded a protester there too, he said. The military clamped a curfew on the camp right after the incident, forcing residents to stay home. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, a group of Jewish settlers from the nearby <LOCATION> Kiryat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arba </LOCATION> settlement were surrounded by stone-throwing youths, the spokesman said. The settlers fired shots in the air until troops arrived, he said, and there were no injuries. Also Saturday, a Palestinian youth arrived at <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>'s Alia hospital with a gunshot wound in his arm, a doctor said. The army confirmed the report but said it was not clear how the youth was shot. In <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, students blocked a main street with flaming tires, boulders and trash cans, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reporters said. They waved outlawed <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags and chanted: `` Our lives for Palestine!'' The students dispersed on army orders, the reporters said. Since anti-Israeli violence broke out in the occupied territories, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> seized in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> War, 175 Palestinians have been slain. One Israeli soldier and one Israeli civilian have been killed. <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> activists, in a leaflet circulated late Friday, urged Arabs to keep the uprising alive and said `` the blood of our martyrs must not be spilled for nothing.'' It called for commercial strikes and a `` day of confrontation with the occupation forces'' on Sunday. The leaflet, signed by the `` <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> of the Upsrising,'' also made its most direct call for attacks on Israeli-appointed <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> mayors who have refused to yield to the militants' demands that they resign. It singled out the mayors of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> towns of <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Bireh </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> protested a cartoon published in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times depicting <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> being turned away from <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops, who told him the city was a closed military area. The cartoon, published March 30, was an apparent reference to the frequent closures imposed by the military in the occupied territories in an effort to quell the uprising. `` In all its history, <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> has never been freer or more open to visitors to holy places than it is now,'' <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> declared in a telegram to the paper earlier this week, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Sevannah </PERSON> <PERSON> Meryn </PERSON> on Friday. The cartoon was one of two that angered <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s consul general in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Tzur </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said. The second cartoon, published April 27, depicted an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldier holding a smoking rifle atop a pile of bullet-ridden bodies. The caption read: `` I'm willing to talk peace, but there are n't any Palestinians to talk peace with!''
