<HEAD>FAA Issues Restrictions For Older 737s After Hawaii Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 2nd graf bgng: The Federal ... and inserts 2 grafs after
7th graf bgng: Farrar said ... to UPDATE with FAA now saying half
of jets are outside of U.S., Boeing comment. Sub 10th graf bgng: In
Hawaii ... to add Aloha total.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s, like the jet that ripped open over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> last week, were restricted Saturday from flying at altitudes above 23,000 feet until they can be inspected for structural defects. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> issued an emergency order for jets in the 737-100 and 737-200 series that have had more than 55,000 flights. The order affects 66 planes, half of them in the fleets of <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> and American airlines, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. The rest belong to international carriers. Federal investigators are focusing on possible structural failure in the <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet that blew open Thursday at 24,000 feet. A flight attendant was swept out of the plane to her death and 61 passengers were injured. Under the airworthiness directive issued by <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON>, the airlines must complete visual inspections of the affected area within the next 500 flights. `` They must inspect the area for cracking, corrosion or de-lamination and if any is found, it must be repaired and the suspect pieces replaced,'' <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. The area to be inspected is the top of the fuselage. In the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> jet, a huge upper section of the 737-200 tore away, leaving passengers exposed to the open skies and forcing the pilot to make an emergency landing. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said that at altitudes of 23,000 feet or below, the pressure between the outside and inside of the aircraft is such that a structural weakness would not cause a failure or damage to the plane. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> originally said that all 66 affected jets belonged to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers. However, he later said that about half of the jets belonged to international airlines. He said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> did not know which ones. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> also did not know which international carriers flew the affected 737s. He said the company would try to find that out Monday. A <ORGANIZATION> Piedmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kress </PERSON>, said from <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, that the airline had already begun inspecting the 17 affected 737-200s in its fleet. He said such inspections were part of the airline's regular maintenance program for the jets and the order would have `` virtually no effect on our operation.'' `` The aircraft is such that we use it on short hauls anyhow and we do n't need to attain that altitude of 23,000 feet,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Goto </PERSON> said he had n't heard of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order and had no immediate comment. <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> has three jets affected by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order, in addition to the one involved in the accident, according to <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> said 16 of its 737s were affected by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> order, and those are used on short-haul West Coast routes that do not require flying above 23,000 feet. Spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> McGregor </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> that the airline would inspect those planes within 48 hours. <PERSON> McGregor </PERSON> called the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> action `` prudent,'' and said, `` We're going to comply with it more quickly than required We're simply going to do it as quickly as we can.'' Last October 5, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> ordered close inspection of the upper skin of the early model <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s because routine inspections had turned up cracks near where sections of sheet metal overlap. The agency warned the problem could cause rapid cabin decompression. The inspections also found metal strips on the fuselage coming loose on some early-model <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s because the lamination was no longer holding. The earlier <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> directive covered the first 291 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s manufactured, of which the Aloha plane was No. 152. It had been in service since 1969. <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has said it conducted the inspections in October as ordered but found nothing that caused alarm. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Boynton </PERSON> said Friday in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> the company has issued service bulletins on the need for periodic inspections for possible cracking or structural weakening because of corrosion of the skin of the older <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s. <PERSON> Boynton </PERSON> said the company's most recent bulletin had been issued two weeks before Thursday's incident. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said Saturday's directive was broader than the one issued in October because the new directive orders visual inspections of the entire top of the fuselage. He said the order will probably mean an increase in fuel costs for the airlines because the higher a jet flies, te more fuel-efficient it is. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nall </PERSON> said Friday that investigators believed the cause of the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident was a structural problem with the <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> jet. He also said the jet had been through 85,000 to 90,000 takeoff-and-landing cycles, and called that `` a high cycle number'' because of the stress caused by repeated expansions and contractions of the fuselage. Earlier, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> asked for inspection of all <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-200 jets that have completed more than 55,000 takeoff and landing cycles. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON> grounded three jets similar in age to the one involved in Thursday's accident.
