<HEAD>Two Underground Solidarity Leaders Leave For Rome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts ages in 2d graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two former underground Solidarity leaders were released from prison Saturday and flew to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> after initially refusing to leave the country. <PERSON> Kornel </PERSON> <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>, 46, and <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON>, 28, were put on a plane to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and arrived in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> Saturday night. The communist government released the two men from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s Rakowiecka prison Saturday in a deal with Roman Catholic church officials <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> had been driven to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s airport to board a flight for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, but the two refused to leave after meeting with family members at the airport. The two were then taken back to the prison but agreed to leave the country after more talks at the prison involving church officials. One of <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>'s daughters, <PERSON> Marta </PERSON>, said the two men were told they could either leave together or remain imprisoned. She said medical reasons played a role in the decision to leave. The two were given multiple exit-and-entry passports and were expected to undergo medical treatment in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. Both apparently are suffering from ulcers and other medical problems. <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>, who was arrested Nov. 9, 1987, was chairman of the militant splinter group Fighting Solidarity. He went underground after martial law was declared in December 1981 and the Solidarity union federation was suspended and subsequently outlawed. In 1982, he formed Fighting Solidarity, which differs from Solidarity because it advocates anti-communist political goals. Solidarity emphasizes social and union issues. <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> headed Fighting Solidarity from the time of <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>'s arrest until his own capture in January. He had been in hiding since 1985. A third, less prominent Fighting Solidarity activist, <PERSON> Krzystof </PERSON> <PERSON> Szymanski </PERSON>, also was released Saturday. <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>'s elder daughter, <PERSON> Anna </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> had agreed to leave the country in a deal worked out by church officials. But after family members at the airport told them about new strikes in the country, they decided to stay. Asked to explain what finally prompted the two men to leave, <PERSON> Marta </PERSON> <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> said, `` We can not give you a full explanation. There were very important arguments and they both finally agreed to go.'' `` There were some personal reasons which had to be taken into account, also a serious danger to <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON>'s health,'' she said. <PERSON> Ewa </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoja </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON>'s girlfriend, said official documents indicated the two men were being released at the recommendation of a commission of prison doctors `` due to the required urgent medical examination, which may also take place abroad.'' She said <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> suffered from ulcers and teeth problems, while <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> had ulcer symptoms, poor eyesight and heart and kidney problems. <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>, speaking with reporters in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, said he and <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> at first did not want to leave <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> because they were not told why they were being sent to the West. He said the issue was settled after they spoke with a secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Aloizj </PERSON> <PERSON> Orszulik </PERSON>. `` We decided to leave for three reasons,'' he said. `` First the medical diagnosis'' that <PERSON> Koldziej </PERSON> might have a tumor, `` secondly the possibility that it might be more difficult in the future for the Polish church to perform these humanitarian acts if we refused, and lastly the assurance that we would be allowed to return whenever we choose.'' <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> said that while in prison he was never told anything about what was happening in the country. `` I only learned something today,'' he said. `` There is an agitation going on that reminds me of August of 1980. ... I believe this pressure will increase and I hope it might lead to a change in government.'' In August 1980, nationwide strikes led to the creation of Solidarity. It was chartered by the government and became the first independent union federation in the Soviet bloc but was banned after the December 1981 crackdown. Authorities alleged that <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> were part of a ring that attempted to smuggle equipment intended for terrorist use from <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. They were never formally charged. In a statement in November, <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON> denied the allegations. In September 1986, the communist government issued a broad amnesty for political prisoners. Since then, all political activists jailed have been held on criminal charges. In another development, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorny </PERSON>, the Solidarity leader in the southern <LOCATION> Silesian </LOCATION> industrial region was released after an appeals court on Friday suspended his sentence, Solidarity sources said. <PERSON> Gorny </PERSON> was serving an 18-month sentence at a prison in <LOCATION> Katowice </LOCATION> after being convicted of failing to pay alimony and using false identity cards. He staged a hunger strike in February to protest against his sentence.
