<HEAD>One Strike Settled, Second Continues At Steel Mill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf ``In the...'' to UPDATE with
police patrolling Krakow and Warsaw.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Strikers occupying a machinery plant in southeast <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> ended their sit-in Saturday after apparently winning promises of higher pay, but a walkout by thousands of steel workers persisted with no end in sight. The developments came as the Polish government prepared for its big May Day celebrations. Solidarity, the banned trade union federation, called for nationwide protests to mark the nation's biggest official holiday In the history of the communist government, there has never been a large-scale strike in progress on May Day. Strike leaders said dozens of police vans and vehicles including water cannons moved into positions near the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> steel mill in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> late Saturday. There were also large numbers of police in other parts of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> in an apparent show of strength before May Day. More than 40 opposition activists were rounded up by police to prevent them from taking part in the holiday protests, said <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Romaszewski </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Solidarity spokesman. One of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s senior anti-government activists, <PERSON> Kornel </PERSON> <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON>, founder of the splinter dissident group Fighting Solidarity, was freed from prison nearly six months after his arrest through apparent negotiations by the country's powerful Roman Catholic church. <PERSON> Morawiecki </PERSON> was freed with <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolodziej </PERSON>, another member of Fighting Solidarity. The two men were flown to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> after initially refusing to leave. A strike by what organizers said was about 15,000 workers at the <LOCATION> Lenin </LOCATION> steel mill in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> entered its fifth day with no sign of a breakthrough. The 7,000 striking workers occupying a heavy machinery plant at <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, about 150 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, left the factory Saturday at about 2 p.m. after management agreed to their pay demands, said <PERSON> Grzegorz </PERSON> <PERSON> Surdy </PERSON>, a spokesman for the strikers. The Rev. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Niemiec </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic priest in <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, said the strikers received nothing in writing but that their demands were expected to be met. The state-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> also reported the one-day strike ended but denied there were any negotiations with the strikers. `` In view of the illegal character of the protest action, no negotiations had been held with the striking group,'' the report said. The labor crisis began Monday and is the most serious to confront <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since the December 1981 declaration of martial law and the banning of Solidarity. In a positive development for the government, <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s tram drivers ignored a Solidarity call for a strike Saturday. Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> was to address the nation during the May Day celebration in the capital of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, which was festooned with banners, red party flags and red-and-white national colors in the country's biggest official holiday. The holiday is dedicated to working people and in recent years has been an occasion for sometimes violent protests for Solidarity. Surdy, a student and twice-jailed Solidarity activist, said Saturday he was surprised that authorities had not attempted to stop the <ORGANIZATION> Nowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Huta </ORGANIZATION> strike before the holiday. In a communique issued through the Polish news agency <ORGANIZATION> Interpress </ORGANIZATION>, the plant management said that as of Saturday, it would begin docking strikers' pay and would close down restaurants and snack bars on the plant grounds. In an apparent hardening of the positions of strikers, three fired Solidarity activists _ including <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Gil </PERSON>, the former head of the Solidarity at the plant _ were named to the strike committee. One of the committee's demands is that the three be rehired. Unlike <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s last wave of labor unrest in 1980-81, which gave rise to Solidarity, the workers did not cover the plant with banners or mix political and economic demands. Photographs taken in work areas inside the plant showed workers reading newsapers, sleeping or talking on the telephone. After four days of the strike `` there is weariness and already a little boredom,'' <PERSON> Surdy </PERSON> said, but he emphasized that workers intended to stay off the jobs `` until our demands are met.'' Besides the reinstatement of the fired workers, the steel workers are demanding an immediate 50 percent raise on the average salary of $ 105 a month. At <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION>, where the occupation strike began Friday, the demands included a $ 50 monthly raise, reinstatement of coal allowances and release and rehiring of three other dismissed Solidarity activists. Church sources said earlier Saturday that one of the Solidarity activists had been freed from detention. Solidarity last month urged that May 1 be `` a day of protest'' against the nationwide price increases that have raised prices 42 percent in the first three months of 1988. Union activists applied for permission to march Sunday in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> but were turned down. However, opposiiton sources said the march was planned anyway.
