<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> responded to criticism from Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Saturday, saying `` I think maybe it's time for him to stop criticizing others,'' and defended his leadership ability against rival <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s sharpened charges. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential front-runner, answered the increasing criticism from his competitors only when questioned by reporters. He had avoided any mention of his rivals during a day of campaigning in two states. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor pointed to his state's economic record in trying to deflect <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s suggestion that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was offering only a managerial approach to governing and lacked the leadership abilities that he provides. `` When it comes to leadership, I'm very proud of the fact that I'm governor of a state which is generally viewed to be a state that's way out front,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` My kind of leadership is as a doer, and not a talker.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has also come under fire from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who a day earlier charged <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> with `` waffling all over the field'' in his reaction to the administration's decision to attack Iranian positions in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. He was asked about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s comments that he has `` cannon fodder'' to use against <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the fall, suggesting it was some unknown evidence from the governor's administration in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> `` I really do n't think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are interested in what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> thinks of me and I think of him and whether he's got cannon fodder or whatever it is that he's got,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said `` I think maybe it's time for him to stop criticizing others and to begin to address some fundamental issues that face this country,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. Running with a big delegate lead and confident of his standing in the remaining primaries, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has campaigned cautiously and strived to avoid the suggestion of acrimony. His campaign schedule has been carried out in a manner that has limited his availability to take questions, while he has delivered speeches repeating familiar themes and exhorting supporters not to become overconfident. Earlier in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told supporters they must take `` this primary seriously.'' The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor took an early morning stroll through an outdoor fruit market in downtown <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> and later spoke to union members at a half-empty labor hall in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> less than an hour after <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> received an enthusiastic response for his speech before the same group. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also spoke to a largely black group in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. He criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's anti-drug efforts and told them his aim was `` to open up that door of opportunity to all citizens, no matter who they are or where they come from or what the color of their skin.'' `` That's really what this campaign is all about,'' he said. He traveled to <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> where he attended the state <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s annual Jefferson-Jackson dinner and planned to visit a high school prom where aides said he would deliver a message on the dangers of drinking and driving. With a large and growing lead in delegates over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and a primary calender strongly in his favor, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has been urging supporters at every stop to ignore the polls and work to produce a large turnout. Standing amid new sofas and tables on the loading dock of a <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> furniture store, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spoke optimistically of winning the nomination but also urged them not to become complacent. `` I want to ask you once again to do everything you can, on those phone banks, in your neighborhoods, with your friends and co-workers, to make sure the people are taking this primary seriously, that they know it is important,'' he said. `` If we work together ... we're going to win in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, we're going to win in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> ... and we're going to win this nomination,'' he said In urging his voters to turn out on Tuesday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> repeatedly referred to his own 1978 re-election defeat in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> despite a one-time lead in the polls. `` It was the most painful experience of my life,'' he told union members in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. He compared the experience to being a worker laid off from his job, although he added that in his case it was his own fault. `` I know what it's like,'' he said.
