<HEAD>Cable TV Industry Enjoying Good Times, But Warning Signs Ahead</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 6th graf to CORRECT Metzenbaum's designation to senator
sted of representative; changes time element to March sted of last
month.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Times are good for cable television. It has become a $ 12 billion industry whose programming is watched in more than half of all American households, and subscribership is continuing to grow. But the industry is also wary of how long this prosperity will last. Cable TV is no longer a highly regulated industry weighted down with debt from stringing cable to build community systems. Most of the systems are built and cable operators have more control than ever over what viewers see and how much they pay. `` It's a very healthy industry; it's never been healthier,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, a media analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Life is good in the cable industry right now.'' But some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> think it may be too good. Lawmakers, prompted by complaints from constituents about rate increases and poor service and the competitive concerns of others in the entertainment industry, have raised the specter of reregulating the cable industry. Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, fired a warning shot at the industry at a congressional hearing in March, saying `` some of us feel we were had'' by a law that freed most cable companies of municipal rate control in January 1987. He and other lawmakers wonder aloud whether cable has become an unregulated monopoly. The threat from <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> `` is a concern you ca n't ignore,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said, and this and other regulatory issues are on the minds of cable operators attending their industry's annual convention here this week. More than 13,000 people were expected to attend the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> convention, which runs from Sunday through Tuesday. Cable TV systems added more than 4 million subscribers in 1987, putting the households receiving cable at 51 percent _ about 45 million. Now that many of cable operators have finished building their systems _ wiring more than 80 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> households _ cable companies are beginning to pay off their debt and have cash to spend on programming. Cable is looking to programming to attract new subscribers, and the industry is encouraged by the success of efforts like <PERSON> Showtime </PERSON>'s critically acclaimed `` It's <PERSON> Garry </PERSON> <PERSON> Shandling </PERSON>'s Show,'' a series that now also airs on the <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> broadcasting network. Home Box Office's `` Dear <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: Letters Home from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'' also received high marks from TV critics, and the Entertainment and <ORGANIZATION> Sports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION>, has landed some big sports contracts, including <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> games. `` Things are going extraordinarily well for cable,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Alter </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Cabletelevision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. `` People are discovering the choice in programming that cable offers.'' Cable systems are adding subscribers at the rate of 1 percent to 2 percent a year, and those with the wire are spending nearly as much time watching programming produced by cable as they do viewing programs of the three major broadcast networks, he said. Increased viewership boosted cable advertising sales above the $ 1 billion mark last year, and ad revenues are expected to hit $ 1.5 billion this year, he said. Each new subscriber is worth about $ 2,000 to the asset value of many cable systems, he said. `` There is a tremendous incentive on cable to sharpen its marketing skills to build its subscriber base,'' he said. Rates have also risen since deregulation 16 months ago, and that has concerned <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> says prices in some systems have risen by up to 400 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> NCTA </ORGANIZATION>, however, says the average cable subscriber's monthly bill rose 6.7 percent in the first six months after deregulation. While basic service prices rose about 10.6 percent, rates for premium or pay channels like <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> dropped 2.5 percent, according to the study.
