ATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and the non-OPEC group would give at least a modest boost to prices. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, a London-based oil consultant, said prices could rise as much as $ 1 a barrel in the very short term. `` It's sheer genius, as far as getting them over the next two months'' when oil markets were expected to be weak, <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. By June, oil demand in the industrialized countries is expected to pick up a little, putting less pressure on <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> to restrain its production, he said. If the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> talks ended without agreement, however, prices would be expected to fall sharply, analysts said. The proposed mutual cuts in oil output were easy for most <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members to accept, partly because they are so small and of such short duration that it would be virtually impossible to verify whether any of the cuts were actually made. `` The whole thing is a nonsense'' in terms of actually changing the balance of supply and demand, <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> leaders insisted, however, that the proposed cuts would be important. `` If one cuts by -LRB- a combined -RRB- 500,000 barrels a day the market would stabilize,'' <PERSON> Etienne </PERSON> <PERSON> Tchioba </PERSON>, the oil minister of <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, said in an interview. Other cartel officials acknowledged that the proposed cuts were more imagined than real. `` It's only psychological,'' said one senior <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition he not be further identified. The main aim of the proposal was to establish a precedent for mutual production cuts with the non-OPEC nations. If this could be repeated later, or widened to include more independent producers, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> could have an easier time stabilizing oil prices around its target of $ 18 a barrel.
