<FIRST>r a AM-MethodistConvention     04-30 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Methodist Convention,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Convention An Experience In Ecclesiastical Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The once-in-four-years general conference of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> ended the first lap Saturday of a concentrated exercise in ecclesiastical democracy. Like most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Protestant bodies, the church's organizational system is modeled on the nation's representative system, and the process here provided an intensified example of it. So far, it has been preoccupied with preliminary hearings of legislative committees on a range of proposals, including the status of homosexuals in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and a new hymnbook. Decisions will come next week in the second stage of the 11-day conference, which runs through Friday. The group is the top lawmaking body for the approximately 10 million <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodists </ORGANIZATION> in the country, who make up the nation's second-largest <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> denomination after the Southern Baptists They elect, from their regional units, the 996 national delegates, half laity and half clergy. In a sense, they resemble legislators sent by states to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Somewhat like the Congressional Record, a daily, similar-looking publication, the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advocate </ORGANIZATION>, provides a verbatim account of general proceedings and a summary of committee deliberations. There is lobbying here, too, including advocates in the <ORGANIZATION> Cervantes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> hallways who passed out buttons and brochures promoting church establishment of a university in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. That project, costing an estimated $ 20 million and to be located in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, was approved by the conference Saturday. As in the secular political realm, the conference's task involves carving out budgets, and a 14 percent increase is being proposed to $ 100 million annually for national operations. That does n't include the approximately $ 2.5 billion given annually for local and regional activities. Alongside the general conference, or legislative branch, the church's approximately 100 area bishops serve as the executive branch, appointing clergy to pastoral or other duties. The church also has 13 national boards or agencies, somewhat like cabinet-level departments. Bishops have no vote at the legislative conference, but are required to be present, address it, and in rotation, preside over it. In addition to the legislative and executive branches, a nine-member judicial council elected by the conference serves as the church's `` supreme court'' to settle disputes over church law or constitution. The council has a rigorous schedule during the general conference. The cost of the gathering: about $ 2.5 million, including the convention hall rental fee, the delegates' air travel and $ 55 each per day for living expenses.
</TEXT>
