<HEAD>Report: Treatment for Psoriasis Likely to Produce Birth Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new drug for psoriasis is closely related to the acne drug Accutane, and is probably even more likely to produce birth defects when taken by pregnant women, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Sunday editions that at least seven babies have been born with defects to women who had taken the drug <PERSON> Tegison </PERSON>, though no cases have been been recorded in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The drug was licensed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in December 1986, and is used to treat severe cases of psoriasis, whose symptoms include scaly, reddish patches of skin. The newspaper said experts have called for restrictions on the distribution of Tegison like those suggested for Accutane last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tegison </PERSON>, whose generic name is etretinate, can remain dormant in bodily tissues at least two years after it is taken, and can cause birth defects long after a woman stops taking it, Dr. <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> told the Times. Tegison is produced in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hoffman-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> also makes Accutane. `` I think etretinate will be a much bigger problem than Accutane,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Devendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Kochhar </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Jefferson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` The number of women exposed will be less, but etretinate is manyfold more toxic than Accutane.'' <PERSON> Tegison </PERSON> carries a pregnancy warning saying that it has not yet been determined how long a woman must avoid pregnancy after taking the drug. A spokeswoman for <PERSON> Hoffman-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Glynn </PERSON>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that the company was investigating 10 new related compounds for skin treatments. `` So far, pregnancy risk does seem to come with this class of drugs,'' she said. She said the company was considering whether to make the pregnancy warning more prominent on the package. `` Everything we do for Accutane is certainly applicable to <PERSON> Tegison </PERSON>,'' she said. Last week the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> endorsed suggestions by the company that it strengthen its warning on Accutane and make it harder for women to obtain. <PERSON> Tegison </PERSON> and Accutane can cause facial deformities, mental retardation and often lethal heart defects in babies born to users of the drug, the newspaper said.
