<HEAD>Some Crude Flushed Into Open, Easing Part of Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The wildlife casualty toll from a 175,000-gallon oil spill 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> appeared to have peaked Friday, and gusty winds and high tides helped the cleanup, officials said. `` They are n't picking up many more birds at all now, and we do n't expect to get too many more at all,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Brach </PERSON>. Rescuers have recovered about 470 oil-soaked birds and animals since a <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> refinery spilled crude oil into the <PERSON> Peyton </PERSON> <PERSON> Slough </PERSON> on April 23, said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, regional patrol chief for the state Fish and Game Department. Of those, about 200 have died or were found dead, he said. Only about a dozen oily birds were brought to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bird </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> on Friday, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Podvin </PERSON>. For the second consecutive day, wind and high tides pushed about 1,500 gallons of oil from remote inlets where it had been trapped into open water and marshland. Although the spread could threaten other coastal wildlife sanctuaries, it helped the cleanup, authorities said. `` More and more oil is getting flushed from the marshy areas into the -LRB- <LOCATION> Carquinez </LOCATION> -RRB- <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>, but that's actually working for the most part to our advantage because it's making it easier to pick up,'' said <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. Eight skimmer boats removed several oil-sheen patches over a 12-mile section of the strait, <PERSON> Brach </PERSON> said. More winds and high tides were expected to continue pushing oil into the strait over the weekend, he added. The crude also has begun to thicken, turning into tar and making cleanup along shorelines easier, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials said. About 126,000 gallons of the thick crude has been recovered so far, they said. The spill occurred after a pipe used to draw off rainwater broke inside a <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> oil tank, allowing crude to be siphoned out, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> said. The company acknowledged the practice of keeping outtake valves open during storms violated federal regulations. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolb </PERSON>, principal engineer fo the state <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, has estimated the spill could cost <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> $ 4 million, including $ 3 million in penalties.
