<HEAD>Report: Federal Health Insurance Plan Criticized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal employees' health insurance program is inefficient, overpriced and offers inadequate coverage to its 10 million beneficiaries, according to a report presented to the government Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said in Saturday's editions that the report to the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> found that the health plan costs $ 785 million more than it should for the benefits it provides and will only get worse unless changed. `` With our huge number of employees, we should be able to get a really good deal,'' said <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>. `` We do n't have a really good deal. The report on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> _ which covers federal workers, retirees and their dependents _ was prepared by the consulting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Towers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Perrin </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Crosby </LOCATION>. The 28-year-old benefits program has grown to include 480 health plans. The consultants found that those plans compete to attract the healthy and avoid the sick, rather than competing to offer the best benefits at the cheapest rates. The need to attract the healthiest workers means `` no plan can offer high levels of coverage in certain critical areas'' such as mental health, drug abuse or nursing care, the consultants found.
