<HEAD>Allegations about Christian Community Denied by Evangelist</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALTERBORO, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heading north out of town past farms and pine stands, one might never notice the Overcomer Campground _ until recently, when television news vans began clustering at the headquarters of evangelist R.G. Stair's ministry. The attention follows reports by families in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area that their children have abandoned their lives for a Christian cult, and their allegations that cult members ca n't leave because <ORGANIZATION> Stair </ORGANIZATION> controls their money. The allegations are denied by <PERSON> Stair </PERSON>, a 51-year-old <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> native who, like other members of the Faith Cathedral Fellowship, lives in a renovated mobile home set among the tall oaks and pines near this town about 50 miles from <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. `` We have a good lifestyle here,'' he said. `` We believe in the Christian principle of having food and raiment, be content.'' The ministry is headquartered in a nondescript brown-roofed motel building along <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 15. Beside it is a modest brown building, which is the congregation's tabernacle. Worshippers sit on folding white wood chairs each Friday evening and Saturday morning to hear <PERSON> Stair </PERSON>'s sermons of Bible prophecy delivered from a podium on a red-carpeted riser. Behind the podium is a small room in which the evangelist records his radio programs carried on 50 stations nationwide. A few miles farther north is the sect's 74-acre farm, where 37 people are busy farming and renovating house trailers. The farm has a five-acre plot where residents raise everything from turnips to squash and watermelon. Nearby are a kitchen and dining hall where residents gather for prayers and share their meals. Despite the allegations the group espouses survivalism, there's no indication of any weapons or military dress among the residents of the ministry, where a sign requests there be `` No Smoking, No Drinking and No Swearing. A number have their own bank accounts and vehicles. There is no fence, but a free-standing gate at the motel keeps cars from swerving into the parking lot at night. Visitors can stay without charge, but there are some requirements for those who want to stay permanently, <PERSON> Stair </PERSON> said. `` We want to make sure they believe in the Christian faith like we do,'' he said. They must also be debt-free, because `` it's not right for me to take other people's money and pay your debts,'' he added. The ministry takes in about $ 30,000 a month, <PERSON> Stair </PERSON> said, adding he pays about $ 20,000 monthly for radio air time. Since the challenges to his ministry were raised, several stations have taken the fiery Overcomer broadcast off the air. <PERSON> Stair </PERSON> has predicted that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> wo n't complete his term in office, there'll be an economic shakeup beginning next month and there'll be a limited nuclear war before the year is out. `` I believe God speaks to me,'' he said in a broadcast prepared for this weekend. `` That's one of the issues they have taken up with me. But how many of you Christians out there in radio land believe <PERSON> God </PERSON> speaks to you?'' <PERSON> Stair </PERSON> said the religious community is not a survivalist enclave, noting `` we've got a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> base over there -LRB- in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> -RRB- with submarines. If they're going to blow us up, they're going to blow us up. There is no human protection from a nuclear war.'' The sect does have a food storehouse, stocked with several thousand pounds of food. It's for the congregation's use and is also given away to the needy. <PERSON> Stair </PERSON>, who is called <PERSON> Brother </PERSON> <PERSON> Stair </PERSON> by the congregation, was ordained a Methodist minister. Now, he said, `` I wo n't identify with any organized religion. I just call myself a Christian.'' He said the Lord told him to move <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> 30 years ago `` because the safest place for Christians in the end time is going to be the South.'' He has lived in <LOCATION> Walterboro </LOCATION> for 10 years. Much of the recent controversy has centered on the move of <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> McCourt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Drexel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, to the community. <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahern </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> McCourt </PERSON>'s mother, said <PERSON> Stair </PERSON>'s prophecy of a nuclear war inspired them to quickly sell their home and belongings and head to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. She and others in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> area have called for investigations by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. But Mrs. <PERSON> McCourt </PERSON> said, `` We just wanted to move to a quieter place.'' She said the couple had planned to sell their house and, when a buyer offered them $ 60,000 cash, they decided to take it. Real estate agents had earlier offered to list the house for $ 74,000 and $ 65,000, she said. Mrs. <PERSON> McCourt </PERSON>, who is expecting her second child in June, said she leads a different life from her mother. She said she and her husband do n't watch television or go to movies and on vacations were likely to go to Christian retreats. She said when she arrived in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, she called home to let her mother know where the family was. `` All she kept saying was, ` You're sick,''' she said. `` There was no having a conversation.'' But Mrs. <PERSON> McCourt </PERSON> said her mother is welcome to visit. `` I wish she would come down here. We have no malice.'' <PERSON> Stair </PERSON> said that if his critics in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> were to visit, `` There would be no question of whether I'm making their people stay here or not. Whether they would still approve of the lifestyle is a different story.'' <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> McCourt </PERSON> said the family felt it was time for a change long before they had heard of Stair. `` We wanted something more out in the country, a slower way of life,'' he added. In <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> their church group ate together and had church five times a week, so `` our lifestyle has n't changed that much except we lived in the suburbs and we might have had a little bit more,'' he said. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Moratto </PERSON>, another member of the <LOCATION> Walterboro </LOCATION> congregation, worked for a livestock dealer in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for 25 years before coming to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> last summer. `` I feel this is where the Lord would have me to be,'' he said as he cleaned turnips in a sink outside the group kitchen. `` People do it every day in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> _ sell what they have and move about.'' <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>, who originally came from <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said she and her husband and son were living in a <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> bus in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> last winter when they decided to come to <LOCATION> Walterboro </LOCATION>. `` We'd been seeking the Lord's will. He was telling us his will by telling us to come here,'' she said as she helped prepare dinner. Chief Deputy R.F. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Colleton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that in recent weeks, the department had received a number of calls from relatives of members of the community `` We try to contact them and tell them to call home,'' he said. `` We have no indication of wrongdoing,'' he said, adding, `` It's just a situation that bears watching.
