<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 30-May 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>Congress Turns Spotlight on `Junk' Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> turned its spotlight of scrutiny on `` junk'' bonds this past week, and the head of the investment firm that pioneered the controversial issues defended them staunchly. In 6 -LCB- hours of testimony Thursday before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> investigative subcommittee, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON>, the chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, also defended the firm against allegations of manipulation of the $ 160 billion junk bond market. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, a leading Wall Street investment firm, is the granddaddy of the high-yield, high-risk bonds and underwrites around 40 percent of all junk bonds issued. The securities are designed to allow companies without a track record of earnings to get financing based on whether they have sufficient cash flow to pay off their debts. They pay higher interest rates than those of established companies and are viewed as riskier investments. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, chief of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s junk bond trading unit in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, who pioneered the bonds, was a lot less talkative than <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> at a hearing Wednesday before the investigations subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, who has been under investigation for the past year and a half by a federal grand jury that is reported to be probing insider trading, refused to testify and cited his Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination. Behind the spotlight, the junk bond market seems to have quietly risen like a phoenix from the ashes of the October stock market collapse, as worries about a recession have subsided. The resurgence of corporate `` takeover fever'' earlier this year also gave junk bonds a shot in the arm, since many of the issues are used to finance acquisitions. Some of the companies that have used junk bond financing, such as businesses in the steel and chemical industries, have performed well recently _ helped by a weaker dollar that made their exports more attractive. After the crash, there had been concern that failures of vulnerable companies could cast a shadow on the junk bond market. `` There's an ongoing need for high-yield securities,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Waill </PERSON>, a managing director of investment firm <ORGANIZATION> L.F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rothschild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the head of its junk bond research department. <PERSON> Waill </PERSON> believes more funds will be attracted to junk bonds in the coming months, as investors switch big sums of money now parked in money-market funds into high-yield mutual funds featuring junk bonds. The money-market funds, based on prevailing interest rates on <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, have been yielding relatively low returns recently. Junk bonds are purchased mainly by big financial institutions, and most individual investors buy them through high-yield mutual funds. The bad publicity now surrounding the bonds _ with congressional investigators portraying <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> as a greedy firm that elbowed its own clients aside so top employees could profit on hot new issues _ wo n't hurt the market, traders insist. `` This has been going on for 18 months; it's a little anti-climactic by now,'' <PERSON> Waill </PERSON> said, referring to investigations of junk bond trading and the congressional hearings. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel he expects the junk bond market to expand substantially over the next 10 years, since less than 10 percent of the companies that could get financing by issuing the high-yield bonds have done so. In the last 10 years, the market has grown explosively, from less than $ 25 billion in junk bonds in 1977 to around $ 160 billion last year _ or 25 percent of the $ 650 billion corporate debt market. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> pointed to cable television as an example of an industry ripe for the bonds, saying cable companies tend to have low earnings because of their high investment costs initially but also have great profit potential. The average company issuing junk bonds is about 36 years old, has around $ 1 billion in assets and employs more than 4,000 people, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 30-May 1</NOTE>
