<HEAD>Wall Street, Bond Market Ignore Good Economic News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A double dose of good economic news failed to inspire the nation's financial markets, which worried more about inflation and ended the week by heading down. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that its Index of Leading Indicators rose 0.8 percent in March, the second straight big monthly gain. Some economists said the figure eliminated chances of a recession in 1988 and thereby boosted the Republican chances for winning the presidential election. New home sales also rose in March for the second straight month, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The 4 percent gain strengthened arguments that the housing industry has revived following a slump in the aftermath of the October stock market crash. Nevertheless, some analysts said the sales level could fade later this year because of rising mortgage rates, a consequence of a slow upward move in interest rates over the past several weeks. Others said economic strength also means a probable rise in inflation, which could compel the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to tighten credit conditions. It is the rise in inflation that worries investors in the stock and bond markets, which largely ignored the news on the economy Friday and instead retreated. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks dropped 8.95 points to 2,032.33. In the bond market, a sensitive barometer of inflation and interest rate trends, the key 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond lost about $ 1.25 in face amount, and its yield edged up slightly to 9.09 percent. The economic news helped the value of the dollar, which rose slightly against most key currencies. But some traders said the dollar's behavior also was a reaction to the evidence of rising interest rates, which makes dollar-denominated assets more valuable.
</TEXT>
