<HEAD>Crude Down Then Up, Ends Largely Unchanged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices sagged then bounced back in nervous trading that reflected the uncertain outcome of a key <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, a sensitive barometer of price trends, traders remained wary Friday of guessing results of the meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> ministers in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. The ministers were trying to develop a strategy to jointly reduce output with eight non-OPEC producers in order to erase excess supplies from the market. Contracts for June delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, closed 1 cent higher at $ 17.99 per 42-gallon barrel Friday, after having been down as much as 43 cents. Among refined products, wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 0.16 cent per gallon to 51.67 cents, and wholesale heating oil rose 0.82 cent a gallon to 51.79 cents. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, a strategist at the <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> commodities firm, said oil prices dropped sharply early in the session because of what he called carryover selling from Thursday over the lack of significant news from the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting. After prices fell so quickly, some traders saw buying opportunities and the market quickly moved up. That prompted other traders who had sold borrowed oil on the hunch prices would fall to buy it back, a price-boosting influence known as short-covering. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>, an analyst at the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, called the late-session bounceback a `` pre-weekend, short-covering rally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>